{"title_page": "Errol Barrow", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{more citations needed|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox Prime Minister\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Excellent]]\n| name = Errol Walton Barrow\n| honorific-suffix = [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]], [[Queen's Counsel|QC]]\n| image = Errol Barrow.jpg\n| imagesize = 180px\n| office1 = Premier of Barbados\n| monarch1 = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| governor1 = [[Robert Arundell]]\n| term_start1 = 4 December 1961\n| term_end1 = 30 November 1966\n| predecessor1 = [[Hugh Gordon Cummins|Hugh Cummins]]\n| successor1 = Position Abolished\n| office2 = Prime Minister of Barbados\n| order2 = [[List of Prime Ministers of Barbados|1st]]\n| term_start2 = 30 November 1966\n| term_end2 = 8 September 1976\n| term_start3 = 29 May 1986\n| term_end3 = 1 June 1987\n| monarch = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| governor-general2 = [[John Montague Stow]]<br />[[Arleigh Winston Scott]]\n| deputy = \n| predecessor2 = Position Established\n| successor2 = [[J.M.G. (Tom) Adams]]\n| governor-general3 = [[Hugh Springer]]\n| deputy3 = [[Erskine Sandiford]]\n| predecessor3 = [[Bernard St. John]]\n| successor3 = [[Erskine Sandiford]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1920|1|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Saint Lucy, Barbados]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1987|6|1|1920|1|21|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Saint Michael, Barbados]]\n| spouse = [[Carolyn Plaskett|Carolyn Marie Barrow, (nee Plaskett)]]\n| children = Lesley Barrow<br />David O'Neal Barrow<br />Eric Wayne Padmore\n| alma_mater = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Harrison College (Barbados)|Harrison College]]\n* [[Inns of Court]]\n* [[London School of Economics]]}}\n| occupation = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Lawyer]]\n* [[Jurist]]\n* Academic\n* [[Professor]]\n* Author\n* [[Member of Parliament]]\n* Politician}}\n| party = [[Democratic Labour Party (Barbados)|Democratic Labour Party]] (1966-1987)\n| signature = \n| religion = <!--Military service-->\n| allegiance = {{flag|Great Britain|1921}}\n| branch = [[Royal Air Force]]\n| serviceyears = 1940\u20131947\n| rank = [[Flying Officer]]|\n}}\n'''Errol Walton Barrow,''' [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]], [[Queen's Counsel|QC]] (21 January 1920 &ndash; 1 June 1987) was a Caribbean statesman and the [[List of Prime Ministers of Barbados#Prime Ministers (Post-Independence)|first]] [[Prime Minister of Barbados]]. Born into a family of political and civic activists in the parish of [[Saint Lucy, Barbados|Saint Lucy]], he became a WWII aviator, combat veteran, lawyer, politician, gourmet cook and author. \n\n==Errol Walton Barrow's early life==\n\nErrol Walton Barrow was born January 21<sup>st</sup> 1920 in St. Lucy Barbados, the fourth of five children born to the Rev. Reginald Grant Barrow (1889\u20131980) and his wife Ruth Albertha (nee O'Neal) (1884-1939). Ruth was the daughter of a prosperous blacksmith whose success allowed him to purchase the plantation at St. Lucy where Errol was later born.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The life and times of Errol Barrow|last=Morgan|first=Peter|publisher=Caribbean Communications Inc.|year=1994|isbn=|location=Bridgetown, Barbados|pages=12, 13}}</ref>\u00a0 \u00a0\n\nReverend Barrow, an Anglican priest, had been appointed headmaster of the Alleyne school after his sermons as curate of St Lucy parish church brought him into conflict with the island\u2019s ruling class and church hierarchy. His removal from the pulpit did not succeed in curtailing his advocacy and agitation on behalf of poor black laborers on the island. In 1919 after he challenged the financial misappropriations of the white planters who oversaw the school\u2019s endowment, the church summarily transferred him to the island of St. Croix in the US Virgin Islands leaving his wife alone to give birth to their second son at her family home, before she could join her husband with their four infant children.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://barbadostoday.bb/2020/01/03/the-story-of-rev-reginald-grant-barrow/|title=The Story of Rev. Reginald Grant Barrow|date=2020-01-04|website=Barbados Today|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>\n\nAs Parish Priest at Holy Cross Episcopal Church, Rev. Barrow\u2019s brand of what was later termed \u2018liberation theology\u2019, was no better received by church authorities there than it had been in Barbados. By late 1920 he was forced out of Holy Cross and he founded St. Luke AME, the first African Methodist Episcopal Church in the USVI. Although he found a home for his values in the AME church, his theological freedom made him all the more dangerous in the eyes of the island\u2019s authorities and in 1922 he was deported by order of the Governor as an \u201cundesirable\u201d.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nRev. Barrow eventually made his way to New York and became a Bishop in the AME church. Unfortunately, he never reunited with his wife and it was thus that Errol Barrow spent the first six years of his life in St Croix and began his education at the Danish Preparatory School there. He would not see his father again until years later.\n\nRuth Barrow returned to Barbados to raise her five children with the help of her extended family, living with their grandmother Catherine O\u2019Neal in Bridgetown. Her older brother Dr. [[Charles Duncan O'Neal|Charles Duncan O\u2019Neal]] was a prominent physician and activist (later a National Hero of Barbados) who founded the Democratic League and Workingmen\u2019s Association, the first socialist organization in Barbados.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Errol Walton Barrow|last=Vanderpool|first=Tony|date=7 June 1987|work=The Sunday Advocate|access-date=|url-status=live|location=Barbados|edition=Special|page=27}}</ref> Under his fatherly influence, Dr. O\u2019Neal\u2019s philosophies formed the core of the young Errol\u2019s political and social beliefs. Among Errol\u2019s playmates at his grandmother\u2019s house on Crumpton street was his cousin [[Hugh Springer]], later Sir Hugh, Governor General of Barbados and the third member of the family to be named a National Hero.\n\nIn Barbados Errol first attended Wesley Hall Boys School before winning a scholarship to [[Combermere School]], which he attended for one year before being admitted to [https://harrisoncollege.org/ Harrison\u2019s college], then the most prestigious boys school on the island. It was during his schoolboy days that Barrow acquired the nickname \u201cDipper\u2019 ostensibly for his awkward cricket batting style.<ref name=\":0\" /> It was a moniker that would follow him as an affectionate brand well into his political career. After graduating from Harrison Barrow spent a year working as a legal clerk while studying to earn a scholarship to Codrington College, the school from which his father had emerged as its youngest ever graduate in 1919.<ref name=\":1\" /> His mother died in 1939  and he won the Island Scholarship in 1940, but by December of that year he had chosen a different path.\n\n== World War II and The Aftermath ==\nIn December of 1940, Errol Barrow, along with eleven other of his countrymen who became known as 'The Second Barbadian Contingent', enlisted in the [[Royal Air Force]] to serve during [[World War II]].<ref name=\":4\">[http://www.caribbeanaircrew-ww2.com/?p=394 BARROW \u2013 Errol Walton] Caribbean aircrew in the RAF during WW2.</ref><ref>[https://www.rafmuseum.org.uk/research/online-exhibitions/pilots-of-the-caribbean/heroes-and-sheroes/stateman-flying-officer-errol-walton-barrow.aspx Statesman Flying Officer Errol Walton Barrow], Royal (British) Air Force Museum.</ref> His sister Dame [[Nita Barrow]] recounted the event in her eulogy to him at his funeral. <blockquote>\"I as the big sister packed his clothes ready for his move to the College. Then as he was about to leave a couple of days later, he calmly announced that he would not be going to College. 'I'm going to England. I've joined the Royal Air Force.' \"<ref name=\":0\" /></blockquote>After joining the RAF Volunteer Reserve in London as an Aircraftmen 2 (AC2), Barrow underwent initial training for light bomber crews at RAF Benson. He was then stationed at RAF Marham and trained as a wireless operator. By January 1942 he had been promoted to AC1 and thereafter undertook an eighteen-month navigator training course in Canada. Barrow was awarded his Air Navigator wings and promoted to Sergeant on November 25, 1943.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bajanthings.com/flying-officer-errol-walton-barrow-navigator-raf-world-war-ii-and-prime-minister-of-barbados/|title=Errol Barrow PM of Barbados & RAF Navigator WWII|date=2019-03-12|website=BajanThings|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-01-19}}</ref>\n\nAt this point Barrow was united with the men whose lives would become mutually dependent on each other if they were to survive the war: RAF pilot Andrew Leslie Cole and RAAF Wireless/Air gunners Leo Leslie J Schultz and Robert Allen Stewart and RAF Navigator and Bomber Errol Walton Barrow spent four months training for operational missions in Nova Scotia, graduating on April 7th 1944. The newly formed crew returned to England and joined 88 squadron on September 20, 1944, flying Douglass Boston (DB-7) light bombers.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nOver the next six months, Barrow flew 53 operational bombing missions over the European theatre, including support for ground forces during the Battle of the Bulge. At wars end he was appointed as personal navigator to the Commander in Chief of the [[Allied Occupation Zones in Germany|British Zone]] of occupied Germany, Air Chief Marshall Sir [[William Sholto Douglas]]. During that period Barrow rose to the rank of [[Flying Officer]]. Douglas, who later became chairman of British European Airways, remained close to Barrow and made him Godfather to his only child.\n\nHis final RAF posting saw him seconded to the Colonial Office, where he oversaw the education and vocational training initiatives for ex-servicemen from all of the colonial territories.<ref name=\":2\" /> Notably of the twelve men who left Barbados of part of the Second Contingent, six were killed during the war.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nIn September of 1947 he was given special permission by the University of London to study at the [[London School of Economics]] and study Law at the [[Inns of Court]] concurrently, taking degrees in 1950 and1949 respectively. During that time, Barrow also served as Chairman of the Council of Colonial Students where his contemporaries included [[Forbes Burnham]], [[Michael Manley]], [[Pierre Trudeau]], and [[Lee Kwan Yew]]  all destined to become political leaders in their home countries.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Political Career ==\nBarrow returned to Barbados in 1950 and was elected to the [[Parliament of Barbados|Barbados Parliament]] in 1951 as a member of the [[Barbados Labour Party]] (BLP) representing the parish of St. George. Feeling the fever of anti-colonialism he had inculcated during his student days in London, he quickly became dissatisfied by general failure of the incremental approach to change advocated by the party stalwarts and their continued support of imperialist powers. By 1952 he began to openly challenge his party\u2019s policies and by 1955 made a declaration in Parliament stating \u201cI no longer want to be associated with them politically or otherwise\u201d <ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|title=Fathering a nation : Barbados and the legacy of Errol Walton Barrow|others=Hewitt, Guy|isbn=978-1-910553-63-3|location=Hertford|oclc=999629424|year = 2016}}</ref> <sup>:72</sup>\n\nIn April 1955 Barrow and twenty-one other like-minded politicians and activists adopted the Constitution of the [[Democratic Labour Party (Barbados)|Democratic Labour Party]] as a progressive alternative to the BLP. In the 1956 general election, the DLP field sixteen candidates of whom twelve were defeated including the incumbent Barrow in his St. George constituency.<ref name=\":5\" /> <sup>:75</sup>\n\nBarrow returned to parliament in the by-election of 1958 representing the parish of St. John and was elected Chairman of the DLP in1959. In December of 1961, the party won the general election with Barrow as its leader. He then served as Premier of Barbados from 1961 until 1966 when, after leading the country to independence from Great Britain, he became the island\u2019s first Prime Minister. He served continuously in that capacity as well as stints as Minister of Finance, and Minister of Foreign Affairs for the next ten years.\n\nDuring his tenure, the DLP government accelerated industrial development, expanded the tourist industry to reduce the island's economic dependence on sugar, introduced National Health Insurance and Social Security, and implemented free secondary school education.\n\nBarrow was a dedicated proponent of regional integration, spearheading the foundation of the [[Caribbean Free Trade Association]] (CARIFTA) in 1965. Eight years later CARIFTA evolved into the Caribbean Community ([[CARICOM]]), when Barrow, together with Forbes Burnham of [[Guyana]], Dr. [[Eric Williams]] of [[Trinidad & Tobago]] and Michael Manley of [[Jamaica]] enacted the [[Treaty of Chaguaramas]] to bolster political and economic relations between the English-speaking Caribbean territories.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/1987/06/03/barbados-prime-minister-barrow-dies/95c5b5e3-44a4-4c11-a207-117ebf1d7136/ BARBADOS PRIME MINISTER BARROW DIES], June 3, 1987, The Washington Post</ref>\n\nAfter another [[1971 Barbados legislative election|landslide victory]] in 1971, the DLP returned to the electorate in 1976 for a mandate after two years of bitter controversy over constitutional amendments put forth by the government. Barrow, who had invited public comment on the amendments verbally lashed out at those who had been critical of what he viewed as a minor procedural change in the appointment of judges. A general economic downturn that affected most countries in the hemisphere contributed to a shift in public sentiment resulting in the party's [[1976 Barbados legislative election|election]] defeat.\n\nAs an indomitable advocate of Caribbean sovereignty he fiercely opposed interference in Caribbean affairs. As opposition leader in 1983 he spoke out forcefully against the United States [[invasion of Grenada]] and he was scathing in his criticism of other Caribbean leaders who kow-towed to [[Federal government of the United States|Washington]] in the hope of getting economic handouts:\n\n:\"Mr. Seaga (Prime Minister of Jamaica, [[Edward Seaga]]) thinks that the solution to Jamaica's problems is to get [[Ronald Reagan|President Reagan]] to play Santa Claus. I do not believe in Santa Claus.\"\n\nIn May 1986, after 10 years in opposition, Barrow was re-elected as Prime Minister in a [[1986 Barbados legislative election|landslide victory]] in which the DLP won 24 of 27 seats in the [[Barbados House of Assembly|House of Assembly]]. The campaign was notable for an address he gave at a political rally some two weeks before the election which came to be known as the \"Mirror Image\" speech. In it, Barrow rhetorically asked Barbadians what kind of a future they saw for themselves when they looked in the mirror; contrasting a life of menial labour as an \u00e9migr\u00e9 in the developed world, or staying and building a strong and independent Barbados to rival other small states like [[Singapore]].\n\nHis re-election served as a catalyst for resurgent nationalism in the region, which by and large had subordinated itself to U.S. aid policy in the early 1980s. Barrow wasted no time in distancing himself from the \"mendicant mentality\" of his predecessors [[John Michael Geoffrey Manningham Adams|J. M. G. Adams]] and [[Bernard St. John]]. In his first press conference as Prime Minister he referred to Reagan as \"that cowboy in the White House\". In a British interview, he characterized the President of the United States as \"a zombie; he's programmed, a very dangerous person\".\n\nHe chastised Washington for its treatment of not only the Caribbean states, but also of Canada and the United Kingdom, which he described as Barbados' closest allies. His political opponents deemed his attacks on Reagan as \"tactically stupid\", but for most Barbadians, his outspokenness meant that \"The Skipper\" was back.\n\nA year after his re-election, Prime Minister Errol Barrow collapsed and died at his home on 1 June 1987. By an act of Parliament in 1998, Barrow was named as one of the ten [[Barbadian National Heroes|National Heroes of Barbados]].<ref name=\"Parl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.barbadosparliament.com/history.php |title=Parliament's History |author=Parliament of Barbados |year=2009 |publisher=Barbadosparliament.com |accessdate=15 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070523083154/http://www.barbadosparliament.com/history.php |archivedate=23 May 2007 |df=dmy |author-link=Parliament of Barbados }}</ref>\n\n== Personal Life ==\nErrol Barrow was a son of the Rev. Reginald Grant Barrow (1889\u20131980) and Ruth Albertha O'Neal (maiden; 1884\u20131939).  His sister, Dame [[Nita Barrow]], also became a social activist, humanitarian leader and later [[Governor General of Barbados]]. He had three other siblings, and two half-siblings from his father's second marriage.\n\n=== Marriage, and Other Relationships ===\nErrol Barrow married Carolyn Marie Plaskett, the daughter of a prominent American Baptist minister in Orange, NJ on November 18, 1945. Their union produced two children: Lesley (b. 1949 d. 2008) and David (b. 1957). Despite their eventual estrangement the couple never divorced.\n\nIn the late 1950's his relationship with union activist Thelma Padmore produced a son Eric (b. 1960).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://obitmoments.com/obituary/thelma-e-padmore/101/|title=Remembering Thelma E Padmore|website=obitmoments.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref>\n\nIn her autobiography the American singer Nina Simone claimed to have had an affair with Barrow (whose first name she misspells) during the brief period that she lived in Barbados.<ref>{{Cite book|title=I put a spell on you : the autobiography of Nina Simone|last=Simone, Nina, 1933-2003.|date=2003|publisher=Da Capo Press|others=Cleary, Stephen.|isbn=0-306-81327-0|edition=Da Capo Press pbk. ed., 2nd Da Capo Press|location=Cambridge, Mass.|oclc=53048134}}</ref>\n\nDuring the last thirteen years of his life until his death, Barrow lived with socialite Jeanine Leemans.\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Statue of Errol W. Barrow. Bridgetown, Barbados.jpg|150px|thumb|Statue of Errol Barrow at Independence Sq., Bridgetown, Barbados]]\n[[File:Errol Barrow Centre For Creative Imagination (UWI), Barbados-1.jpg|150px|thumb|right|Errol Barrow Centre For Creative Imagination]]\nThe Errol Barrow Centre for Creative Imagination, at the [[University of the West Indies, Cave Hill]] campus, promotes the making, study and appreciation of the arts. It is \"a hub for creative expression and the creative cycle: creation, production, distribution, appreciation and preservation of art\".<ref>[http://www.cavehill.uwi.edu/ebcci/ Errol Barrow Centre for Creative Imagination.]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Politics of Barbados]]\n* [[List of Prime Ministers of Barbados|List of Premiers/Prime Ministers of Barbados]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060224180252/http://www.barbados.gov.bb/errolb.htm Errol Barrow]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060104204501/http://www.silvertorch.com/arts/barrow1.htm Errol Barrow]\n*[http://www.cavehill.uwi.edu/ebcci/ Website for The Errol Barrow Centre for Creative Imagination], at the Cave Hill Campus of UWI.\n*[http://digitalcollections.lib.neu.edu/Greenstone/collect/freedomh The Freedom House Photographs]{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} collection contains images of Errol Barrow in Barbados and in Boston, Massachusetts (Archives and Special Collections of the Northeastern University Libraries in Boston, Massachusetts).\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|bb}}\n{{s-bef|before=*}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Saint George (BB Parliament constituency)|Saint George]]\n|years=[[1951 Barbadian general election|1951]] \u2013 [[1956 Barbadian general election|1956]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=*}}\n{{s-bef|before=*}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Saint John (BB Parliament constituency)|Saint John]]\n|years=[[1958 Barbados by-election|1958]] \u2013 [[1987 Barbados by-election|1987]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[David Thompson (Barbadian politician)]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box|\n before=New position|\n title=[[Prime Minister of Barbados]]|\n after=[[J.M.G. Adams]]|\n years=1966 &ndash; 1976\n}}\n{{succession box|\n before=[[Harold Bernard St. John]]|\n title=[[Prime Minister of Barbados]]|\n after=[[Erskine Sandiford]]|\n years=1986 &ndash; 1987\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{BarbadosPMs}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barrow, Errol}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:People educated at Harrison College (Barbados)]]\n[[Category:1987 deaths]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Barbadian Anglicans]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Barbados]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Democratic Labour Party (Barbados)]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force officers]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Assembly of Barbados]]\n[[Category:Barbadian Queen's Counsel]]\n[[Category:People from Saint Lucy, Barbados]]\n[[Category:People who died in office]]\n[[Category:20th-century Barbadian lawyers]]\n[[Category:Military history of Barbados during World War II]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Honorary Fellows of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:Independence activists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{more citations needed|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox Prime Minister\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Excellent]]\n| name = Errol Walton Barrow\n| honorific-suffix = [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]], [[Queen's Counsel|QC]]\n| image = Errol Barrow.jpg\n| imagesize = 180px\n| office1 = Premier of Barbados\n| monarch1 = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| governor1 = [[Robert Arundell]]\n| term_start1 = 4 December 1961\n| term_end1 = 30 November 1966\n| predecessor1 = [[Hugh Gordon Cummins|Hugh Cummins]]\n| successor1 = Position Abolished\n| office2 = Prime Minister of Barbados\n| order2 = [[List of Prime Ministers of Barbados|1st]]\n| term_start2 = 30 November 1966\n| term_end2 = 8 September 1976\n| term_start3 = 29 May 1986\n| term_end3 = 1 June 1987\n| monarch = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| governor-general2 = [[John Montague Stow]]<br />[[Arleigh Winston Scott]]\n| deputy = \n| predecessor2 = Position Established\n| successor2 = [[J.M.G. (Tom) Adams]]\n| governor-general3 = [[Hugh Springer]]\n| deputy3 = [[Erskine Sandiford]]\n| predecessor3 = [[Bernard St. John]]\n| successor3 = [[Erskine Sandiford]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1920|1|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Saint Lucy, Barbados]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1987|6|1|1920|1|21|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Saint Michael, Barbados]]\n| spouse = [[Carolyn Plaskett|Carolyn Marie Barrow, (nee Plaskett)]]\n| children = Lesley Barrow<br />David O'Neal Barrow<br />Eric Wayne Padmore\n| alma_mater = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Harrison College (Barbados)|Harrison College]]\n* [[Inns of Court]]\n* [[London School of Economics]]}}\n| occupation = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Lawyer]]\n* [[Jurist]]\n* Academic\n* [[Professor]]\n* Author\n* [[Member of Parliament]]\n* Politician}}\n| party = [[Democratic Labour Party (Barbados)|Democratic Labour Party]] (1966-1987)\n| signature = \n| religion = <!--Military service-->\n| allegiance = {{flag|Great Britain|1921}}\n| branch = [[Royal Air Force]]\n| serviceyears = 1940\u20131947\n| rank = [[Flying Officer]]|\n}}\n'''Errol Walton Barrow,''' [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]], [[Queen's Counsel|QC]] (21 January 1920 &ndash; 1 June 1987) was a Caribbean statesman and the [[List of Prime Ministers of Barbados#Prime Ministers (Post-Independence)|first]] [[Prime Minister of Barbados]]. Born into a family of political and civic activists in the parish of [[Saint Lucy, Barbados|Saint Lucy]], he became a WWII aviator, combat veteran, lawyer, politician, gourmet cook and author. \n\n==Errol Walton Barrow's Early Life==\n\nErrol Walton Barrow was born January 21<sup>st</sup> 1920 in St. Lucy Barbados, the fourth of five children born to the Rev. Reginald Grant Barrow (1889\u20131980) and his wife Ruth Albertha (nee O'Neal) (1884-1939). Ruth was the daughter of a prosperous blacksmith whose success allowed him to purchase the plantation at St. Lucy where Errol was later born.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The life and times of Errol Barrow|last=Morgan|first=Peter|publisher=Caribbean Communications Inc.|year=1994|isbn=|location=Bridgetown, Barbados|pages=12, 13}}</ref>\u00a0 \u00a0\n\nReverend Barrow, an Anglican priest, had been appointed headmaster of the Alleyne school after his sermons as curate of St Lucy parish church brought him into conflict with the island\u2019s ruling class and church hierarchy. His removal from the pulpit did not succeed in curtailing his advocacy and agitation on behalf of poor black laborers on the island. In 1919 after he challenged the financial misappropriations of the white planters who oversaw the school\u2019s endowment, the church summarily transferred him to the island of St. Croix in the US Virgin Islands leaving his wife alone to give birth to their second son at her family home, before she could join her husband with their four infant children.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://barbadostoday.bb/2020/01/03/the-story-of-rev-reginald-grant-barrow/|title=The Story of Rev. Reginald Grant Barrow|date=2020-01-04|website=Barbados Today|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>\n\nAs Parish Priest at Holy Cross Episcopal Church, Rev. Barrow\u2019s brand of what was later termed \u2018liberation theology\u2019, was no better received by church authorities there than it had been in Barbados. By late 1920 he was forced out of Holy Cross and he founded St. Luke AME, the first African Methodist Episcopal Church in the USVI. Although he found a home for his values in the AME church, his theological freedom made him all the more dangerous in the eyes of the island\u2019s authorities and in 1922 he was deported by order of the Governor as an \u201cundesirable\u201d.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nRev. Barrow eventually made his way to New York and became a Bishop in the AME church. Unfortunately, he never reunited with his wife and it was thus that Errol Barrow spent the first six years of his life in St Croix and began his education at the Danish Preparatory School there. He would not see his father again until years later.\n\nRuth Barrow returned to Barbados to raise her five children with the help of her extended family, living with their grandmother Catherine O\u2019Neal in Bridgetown. Her older brother Dr. [[Charles Duncan O'Neal|Charles Duncan O\u2019Neal]] was a prominent physician and activist (later a National Hero of Barbados) who founded the Democratic League and Workingmen\u2019s Association, the first socialist organization in Barbados.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Errol Walton Barrow|last=Vanderpool|first=Tony|date=7 June 1987|work=The Sunday Advocate|access-date=|url-status=live|location=Barbados|edition=Special|page=27}}</ref> Under his fatherly influence, Dr. O\u2019Neal\u2019s philosophies formed the core of the young Errol\u2019s political and social beliefs. Among Errol\u2019s playmates at his grandmother\u2019s house on Crumpton street was his cousin [[Hugh Springer]], later Sir Hugh, Governor General of Barbados and the third member of the family to be named a National Hero.\n\nIn Barbados Errol first attended Wesley Hall Boys School before winning a scholarship to [[Combermere School]], which he attended for one year before being admitted to [https://harrisoncollege.org/ Harrison\u2019s college], then the most prestigious boys school on the island. It was during his schoolboy days that Barrow acquired the nickname \u201cDipper\u2019 ostensibly for his awkward cricket batting style.<ref name=\":0\" /> It was a moniker that would follow him as an affectionate brand well into his political career. After graduating from Harrison Barrow spent a year working as a legal clerk while studying to earn a scholarship to Codrington College, the school from which his father had emerged as it\u2019s youngest ever graduate in 1919<ref name=\":1\" />. His mother died in 1939  and he won the Island Scholarship in 1940, but by December of that year he had chosen a different path.\n\n== World War II and The Aftermath ==\nIn December of 1940 Errol Barrow, along with eleven other of his countrymen who became known as 'The Second Barbadian Contingent', enlisted in the [[Royal Air Force]] to serve during [[World War II]].<ref name=\":4\">[http://www.caribbeanaircrew-ww2.com/?p=394 BARROW \u2013 Errol Walton] Caribbean aircrew in the RAF during WW2.</ref><ref>[https://www.rafmuseum.org.uk/research/online-exhibitions/pilots-of-the-caribbean/heroes-and-sheroes/stateman-flying-officer-errol-walton-barrow.aspx Statesman Flying Officer Errol Walton Barrow], Royal (British) Air Force Museum.</ref> His sister Dame [[Nita Barrow]] recounted the event in her eulogy to him at his funeral. <blockquote>\"I as the big sister packed his clothes ready for his move to the College. Then as he was about to leave a couple of days later, he calmly announced that he would not be going to College. 'I'm going to England. I've joined the Royal Air Force.' \"<ref name=\":0\" /></blockquote>After joining the RAF Volunteer Reserve in London as an Aircraftmen 2 (AC2), Barrow underwent initial training for light bomber crews at RAF Benson. He was then stationed at RAF Marham and trained as a wireless operator. By January 1942 he had been promoted to AC1 and thereafter undertook an eighteen-month navigator training course in Canada. Barrow was awarded his Air Navigator wings and promoted to Sergeant on November 25th 1943.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bajanthings.com/flying-officer-errol-walton-barrow-navigator-raf-world-war-ii-and-prime-minister-of-barbados/|title=Errol Barrow PM of Barbados & RAF Navigator WWII|date=2019-03-12|website=BajanThings|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-01-19}}</ref>\n\nAt this point Barrow was united with the men whose lives would become mutually dependent on each other if they were to survive the war: RAF pilot Andrew Leslie Cole and RAAF Wireless/Air gunners Leo Leslie J Schultz and Robert Allen Stewart and RAF Navigator and Bomber Errol Walton Barrow spent four months training for operational missions in Nova Scotia, graduating on April 7th 1944. The newly formed crew returned to England and joined 88 squadron on September 20th 1944, flying Douglass Boston (DB-7) light bombers.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nOver the next six months Barrow flew 53 operational bombing missions over the European theatre, including support for ground forces during the Battle of the Bulge. At wars end he was appointed as personal navigator to the Commander in Chief of the [[Allied Occupation Zones in Germany|British Zone]] of occupied Germany, Air Chief Marshall Sir [[William Sholto Douglas]]. During that period Barrow rose to the rank of [[Flying Officer]]. Douglas, who later became chairman of British European Airways, remained close to Barrow and made him Godfather to his only child.\n\nHis final RAF posting saw him seconded to the Colonial Office, where he oversaw the education and vocational training initiatives for ex-servicemen from all of the colonial territories.<ref name=\":2\" /> Notably of the twelve men who left Barbados of part of the Second Contingent, six were killed during the war.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nIn September of 1947 he was given special permission by the University of London to study at the [[London School of Economics]] and study Law at the [[Inns of Court]] concurrently, taking degrees in 1950 and1949 respectively. During that time, Barrow also served as Chairman of the Council of Colonial Students where his contemporaries included [[Forbes Burnham]], [[Michael Manley]], [[Pierre Trudeau]], and [[Lee Kwan Yew]]  all destined to become political leaders in their home countries.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Political Career ==\nBarrow returned to Barbados in 1950 and was elected to the [[Parliament of Barbados|Barbados Parliament]] in 1951 as a member of the [[Barbados Labour Party]] (BLP) representing the parish of St. George. Feeling the fever of anti-colonialism he had inculcated during his student days in London, he quickly became dissatisfied by general failure of the incremental approach to change advocated by the party stalwarts and their continued support of imperialist powers. By 1952 he began to openly challenge his party\u2019s policies and by 1955 made a declaration in Parliament stating \u201cI no longer want to be associated with them politically or otherwise\u201d <ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|title=Fathering a nation : Barbados and the legacy of Errol Walton Barrow|others=Hewitt, Guy|isbn=978-1-910553-63-3|location=Hertford|oclc=999629424|year = 2016}}</ref> <sup>:72</sup>\n\nIn April 1955 Barrow and twenty-one other like-minded politicians and activists adopted the Constitution of the [[Democratic Labour Party (Barbados)|Democratic Labour Party]] as a progressive alternative to the BLP. In the 1956 general election, the DLP field sixteen candidates of whom twelve were defeated including the incumbent Barrow in his St. George constituency.<ref name=\":5\" /> <sup>:75</sup>\n\nBarrow returned to parliament in the by-election of 1958 representing the parish of St. John and was elected Chairman of the DLP in1959. In December of 1961 the party won the general election with Barrow as its leader. He then served as Premier of Barbados from 1961 until 1966 when, after leading the country to independence from Great Britain, he became the island\u2019s first Prime Minister. He served continuously in that capacity as well as stints as Minister of Finance, and Minister of Foreign Affairs for the next ten years.\n\nDuring his tenure the DLP government accelerated industrial development, expanded the tourist industry to reduce the island's economic dependence on sugar, introduced National Health Insurance and Social Security, and implemented free secondary school education.\n\nBarrow was a dedicated proponent of regional integration, spearheading the foundation of the [[Caribbean Free Trade Association]] (CARIFTA) in 1965. Eight years later CARIFTA evolved into the Caribbean Community ([[CARICOM]]), when Barrow, together with Forbes Burnham of [[Guyana]], Dr. [[Eric Williams]] of [[Trinidad & Tobago]] and Michael Manley of [[Jamaica]] enacted the [[Treaty of Chaguaramas]] to bolster political and economic relations between the English-speaking Caribbean territories.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/1987/06/03/barbados-prime-minister-barrow-dies/95c5b5e3-44a4-4c11-a207-117ebf1d7136/ BARBADOS PRIME MINISTER BARROW DIES], June 3, 1987, The Washington Post</ref>\n\nAfter another [[1971 Barbados legislative election|landslide victory]] in 1971, the DLP returned to the electorate in 1976 for a mandate after two years of bitter controversy over constitutional amendments put forth by the government. Barrow, who had invited public comment on the amendments verbally lashed out at those who had been critical of what he viewed as a minor procedural change in the appointment of judges. A general economic downturn which affected most countries in the hemisphere contributed to a shift in public sentiment resulting in the party's [[1976 Barbados legislative election|election]] defeat.\n\nAs an indomitable advocate of Caribbean sovereignty he fiercely opposed interference in Caribbean affairs. As opposition leader in 1983 he spoke out forcefully against the United States [[invasion of Grenada]] and he was scathing in his criticism of other Caribbean leaders who kow-towed to [[Federal government of the United States|Washington]] in the hope of getting economic handouts:\n\n:\"Mr. Seaga (Prime Minister of Jamaica, [[Edward Seaga]]) thinks that the solution to Jamaica's problems is to get [[Ronald Reagan|President Reagan]] to play Santa Claus. I do not believe in Santa Claus.\"\n\nIn May 1986, after 10 years in opposition, Barrow was re-elected as Prime Minister in a [[1986 Barbados legislative election|landslide victory]] in which the DLP won 24 of 27 seats in the [[Barbados House of Assembly|House of Assembly]]. The campaign was notable for an address he gave at a political rally some two weeks before the election which came to be known as the \"Mirror Image\" speech. In it, Barrow rhetorically asked Barbadians what kind of a future they saw for themselves when they looked in the mirror; contrasting a life of menial labour as an \u00e9migr\u00e9 in the developed world, or staying and building a strong and independent Barbados to rival other small states like [[Singapore]].\n\nHis re-election served as a catalyst for resurgent nationalism in the region, which by and large had subordinated itself to U.S. aid policy in the early 1980s. Barrow wasted no time in distancing himself from the \"mendicant mentality\" of his predecessors [[John Michael Geoffrey Manningham Adams|J. M. G. Adams]] and [[Bernard St. John]]. In his first press conference as Prime Minister he referred to Reagan as \"that cowboy in the White House\". In a British interview he characterized the  President of the United States as \"a zombie; he's programmed, a very dangerous person\".\n\nHe chastised Washington for its treatment of not only the Caribbean states, but also of Canada and the United Kingdom, which he described as Barbados' closest allies. His political opponents deemed his attacks on Reagan as \"tactically stupid\", but for most Barbadians his outspokenness meant that \"The Skipper\" was back.\n\nA year after his re-election, Prime Minister Errol Barrow collapsed and died at his home on 1 June 1987. By an act of Parliament in 1998, Barrow was named as one of the ten [[Barbadian National Heroes|National Heroes of Barbados]].<ref name=\"Parl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.barbadosparliament.com/history.php |title=Parliament's History |author=Parliament of Barbados |year=2009 |publisher=Barbadosparliament.com |accessdate=15 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070523083154/http://www.barbadosparliament.com/history.php |archivedate=23 May 2007 |df=dmy |author-link=Parliament of Barbados }}</ref>\n\n== Personal Life ==\nErrol Barrow was a son of the Rev. Reginald Grant Barrow (1889\u20131980) and Ruth Albertha O'Neal (maiden; 1884\u20131939).  His sister, Dame [[Nita Barrow]], also became a social activist, humanitarian leader and later [[Governor General of Barbados]]. He had three other siblings, and two half-siblings from his father's second marriage.\n\n=== Marriage, and Other Relationships ===\nErrol Barrow married Carolyn Marie Plaskett, the daughter of a prominent American Baptist minister in Orange, NJ on November 18, 1945. Their union produced two children: Lesley (b. 1949 d. 2008) and David (b. 1957). Despite their eventual estrangement the couple never divorced.\n\nIn the late 1950's his relationship with union activist Thelma Padmore produced a son Eric (b. 1960).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://obitmoments.com/obituary/thelma-e-padmore/101/|title=Remembering Thelma E Padmore|website=obitmoments.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref>\n\nIn her autobiography the American singer Nina Simone claimed to have had an affair with Barrow (whose first name she misspells) during the brief period that she lived in Barbados.<ref>{{Cite book|title=I put a spell on you : the autobiography of Nina Simone|last=Simone, Nina, 1933-2003.|date=2003|publisher=Da Capo Press|others=Cleary, Stephen.|isbn=0-306-81327-0|edition=Da Capo Press pbk. ed., 2nd Da Capo Press|location=Cambridge, Mass.|oclc=53048134}}</ref>\n\nDuring the last thirteen years of his life until his death Barrow lived with socialite Jeanine Leemans.\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Statue of Errol W. Barrow. Bridgetown, Barbados.jpg|150px|thumb|Statue of Errol Barrow at Independence Sq., Bridgetown, Barbados]]\n[[File:Errol Barrow Centre For Creative Imagination (UWI), Barbados-1.jpg|150px|thumb|right|Errol Barrow Centre For Creative Imagination]]\nThe Errol Barrow Centre for Creative Imagination, at the [[University of the West Indies, Cave Hill]] campus, promotes the making, study and appreciation of the arts. It is \"a hub for creative expression and the creative cycle: creation, production, distribution, appreciation and preservation of art\".<ref>[http://www.cavehill.uwi.edu/ebcci/ Errol Barrow Centre for Creative Imagination.]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Politics of Barbados]]\n* [[List of Prime Ministers of Barbados|List of Premiers/Prime Ministers of Barbados]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060224180252/http://www.barbados.gov.bb/errolb.htm Errol Barrow]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060104204501/http://www.silvertorch.com/arts/barrow1.htm Errol Barrow]\n*[http://www.cavehill.uwi.edu/ebcci/ Website for The Errol Barrow Centre for Creative Imagination], at the Cave Hill Campus of UWI.\n*[http://digitalcollections.lib.neu.edu/Greenstone/collect/freedomh The Freedom House Photographs]{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} collection contains images of Errol Barrow in Barbados and in Boston, Massachusetts (Archives and Special Collections of the Northeastern University Libraries in Boston, Massachusetts).\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|bb}}\n{{s-bef|before=*}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Saint George (BB Parliament constituency)|Saint George]]\n|years=[[1951 Barbadian general election|1951]] \u2013 [[1956 Barbadian general election|1956]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=*}}\n{{s-bef|before=*}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Saint John (BB Parliament constituency)|Saint John]]\n|years=[[1958 Barbados by-election|1958]] \u2013 [[1987 Barbados by-election|1987]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[David Thompson (Barbadian politician)]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box|\n before=New position|\n title=[[Prime Minister of Barbados]]|\n after=[[J.M.G. Adams]]|\n years=1966 &ndash; 1976\n}}\n{{succession box|\n before=[[Harold Bernard St. John]]|\n title=[[Prime Minister of Barbados]]|\n after=[[Erskine Sandiford]]|\n years=1986 &ndash; 1987\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{BarbadosPMs}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barrow, Errol}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:People educated at Harrison College (Barbados)]]\n[[Category:1987 deaths]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Barbadian Anglicans]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Barbados]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Democratic Labour Party (Barbados)]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force officers]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Assembly of Barbados]]\n[[Category:Barbadian Queen's Counsel]]\n[[Category:People from Saint Lucy, Barbados]]\n[[Category:People who died in office]]\n[[Category:20th-century Barbadian lawyers]]\n[[Category:Military history of Barbados during World War II]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Honorary Fellows of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:Independence activists]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "it's \u2192 its; manual of style edits", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Errol_Barrow"}
{"title_page": "Green Elephant Vegetarian Bistro", "text_new": "The Green Elephant Vegetarian Bistro is a pan-Asian, [[Vegetarianism|vegetarian]] restaurant in [[Portland, Maine]] that opened in 2007 in the city's [[Arts District (Portland, Maine)|Arts District]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.travelandleisure.com/trip-ideas/maines-best-restaurants-for-vegetarians|title=Maine\u2019s Best Restaurants for Vegetarians|last=Brian|first=Kevin|date=2015-06-08|website=Travel + Leisure|language=EN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> A second restaurant is located in [[Portsmouth, New Hampshire]]. \n\n=== History ===\nThe restaurant was opened by chef Dan Sriprasert and business partner Bob Wongsaichua at 608 Congress Street across from the State Theatre building. Sriprasert and Wongsaichua also own Boda, a Thai restaurant located on Congress Street, and a second Green Elephant Vegetarian Bistro in [[Portsmouth, New Hampshire]]. Born in Thailand, Sriprasert said green stands for vegetarian food and elephants are considered lucky..<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themainemag.com/blog/eat-maine-blog/2020-green-elephant-portland/|title=Green Elephant, Portland|last=Anderson|first=Amy K.|date=2012-09-20|website=The Maine Mag|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> \n\n=== Menu ===\nThe menu is appetizers, stir fries, curries, noodle dishes and desserts. All the food is vegetarian and most is vegan. \n\n=== Reception ===\nThe restaurant doesn't take reservations and people sometimes wait outside for tables. In 2012, [[The Boston Globe]] travel writer Hilary Nangle said the restaurant \"has persuaded many carnivores that going veggie does not mean sacrificing flavor.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Nangle|first=Hilary|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/travel/2012/04/28/maine-restaurants-where-vegetarian-fare-fills-plate-maine-restaurants-where-veggies-reign/Blys2jetRRnK6uzPhzQibI/story.html|title=10 Maine restaurants where vegetarians reign|date=2012-04-29|work=The Boston Globe|access-date=2020-04-01|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2016, the [[Portland Press Herald|Maine Sunday Telegram']]<nowiki/>s restaurant reviewer James H. Schwartz gave the restaurant three stars and wrote: \"It\u2019s fun, congenial and healthful, an easy place for vegetarians, dedicated carnivores \u2013 and the rest of us \u2013 to enjoy.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressherald.com/2016/01/24/even-meat-lovers-will-find-plenty-to-like-at-green-elephant-an-asian-vegetarian-bistro-in-portland/|title=Dine Out Maine: Green Elephant in Portland|last=Schwartz|first=James H.|date=2016-01-24|website=Press Herald|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> In 2020, the [[Portland Press Herald]]'s vegan food writer Avery Yale Kamila called the restaurant Maine's \"reigning vegetarian restaurant queen.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressherald.com/2020/01/19/portlands-vegan-restaurant-scene-is-red-hot/|title=Vegan Kitchen: Portland\u2019s vegan restaurant scene is red-hot|last=Kamila|first=Avery Yale|date=2020-01-19|website=Press Herald|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n=== References ===\n[[Category:Vegetarian restaurants]]\n[[Category:Maine]]\n[[Category:Portland, Maine]]\n[[Category:Thai restaurants]]\n[[Category:Vegan restaurants in the United States]]\n[[Category:Restaurants in Maine]]\n", "text_old": "The Green Elephant Vegetarian Bistro is a pan-Asian, [[Vegetarianism|vegetarian]] restaurant in [[Portland, Maine]] that opened in 2007 in the city's [[Arts District (Portland, Maine)|Arts District]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.travelandleisure.com/trip-ideas/maines-best-restaurants-for-vegetarians|title=Maine\u2019s Best Restaurants for Vegetarians|last=Brian|first=Kevin|date=2015-06-08|website=Travel + Leisure|language=EN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> A second restaurant is located in [[Portsmouth, New Hampshire]]. \n\n=== History ===\nThe restaurant was opened by chef Dan Sriprasert and business partner Bob Wongsaichua at 608 Congress Street across from the State Theatre building. Sriprasert and Wongsaichua also own Boda, a Thai restaurant located on Congress Street, and a second Green Elephant Vegetarian Bistro in [[Portsmouth, New Hampshire]]. Born in Thailand, Sriprasert said green stands for vegetarian food and elephants are considered lucky..<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themainemag.com/blog/eat-maine-blog/2020-green-elephant-portland/|title=Green Elephant, Portland|last=Anderson|first=Amy K.|date=2012-09-20|website=The Maine Mag|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> \n\n=== Menu ===\nThe menu is appetizers, stir fries, curries, noodle dishes and desserts. All the food is vegetarian and most is vegan. \n\n=== Reception ===\nThe restaurant doesn't take reservations and people sometimes wait outside for tables. In 2012, [[The Boston Globe]] travel writer Hilary Nangle said the restaurant \"has persuaded many carnivores that going veggie does not mean sacrificing flavor.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Nangle|first=Hilary|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/travel/2012/04/28/maine-restaurants-where-vegetarian-fare-fills-plate-maine-restaurants-where-veggies-reign/Blys2jetRRnK6uzPhzQibI/story.html|title=10 Maine restaurants where vegetarians reign|date=2012-04-29|work=The Boston Globe|access-date=2020-04-01|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2016, the [[Portland Press Herald|Maine Sunday Telegram']]<nowiki/>s restaurant reviewer James H. Schwartz gave the restaurant three stars and wrote: \"It\u2019s fun, congenial and healthful, an easy place for vegetarians, dedicated carnivores \u2013 and the rest of us \u2013 to enjoy.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressherald.com/2016/01/24/even-meat-lovers-will-find-plenty-to-like-at-green-elephant-an-asian-vegetarian-bistro-in-portland/|title=Dine Out Maine: Green Elephant in Portland|last=Schwartz|first=James H.|date=2016-01-24|website=Press Herald|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> In 2020, the [[Portland Press Herald]]'s vegan food writer Avery Yale Kamila called the restaurant Maine's \"reigning vegetarian restaurant queen.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressherald.com/2020/01/19/portlands-vegan-restaurant-scene-is-red-hot/|title=Vegan Kitchen: Portland\u2019s vegan restaurant scene is red-hot|last=Kamila|first=Avery Yale|date=2020-01-19|website=Press Herald|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n=== References ===\n<br />\n[[Category:Vegetarian restaurants]]\n[[Category:Maine]]\n[[Category:Portland, Maine]]\n[[Category:Thai restaurants]]\n[[Category:Vegan restaurants in the United States]]\n[[Category:Restaurants in Maine]]\n", "name_user": "BrikDuk", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Green_Elephant_Vegetarian_Bistro"}
{"title_page": "Robert-Falcon Ouellette", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name             =Robert-Falcon Ouellette\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image            = \n| imagesize        = 200px\n| riding           = [[Winnipeg Centre]]\n| parliament       = Canadian\n| term_start       =October 19, 2015\n| term_end         = October 21, 2019\n| predecessor      =[[Pat Martin]]\n| successor        = [[Leah Gazan]]\n| birth_date       ={{birth date and age|1976|11|22}}\n| birth_place      =[[Calgary]], [[Alberta]], Canada\n| profession       = Anthropologist\n| party            = [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]]\n| residence        = [[Downtown Winnipeg|West Broadway, Winnipeg, Manitoba]]\n| footnotes        = \n| alma_mater       = [[Universit\u00e9 Laval]] <small>([[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]], [[Master of Arts|M.A.]])</small><br />[[University of Calgary]] <small>([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]])</small>\n| education        = Doctor of Philosophy, Anthropology\n<!--Military service-->\n| allegiance         = [[Canadian Forces]]\n| branch             = [[Royal Canadian Navy]]\n| rank               = Petty Officer 1st class\n| unit               = [[HMCS Chippawa]]\n| serviceyears       = 1992-present\n|}}\n'''Robert-Falcon Ouellette''' (born November 22, 1976) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] politician, who also goes by the initials of RFO or simply called The Falcon, who represented the [[electoral district (Canada)|riding]] of [[Winnipeg Centre]] in the [[House of Commons of Canada]] for one term. He was previously a candidate for [[Mayor of Winnipeg]] in the [[2014 Manitoba municipal elections|2014 municipal election]], finishing third.\n\nOf mixed [[French Canadian|French]] and Cree descent, Ouellette was a veteran of nearly twenty years in the [[Canadian Forces]] and a university professor before his entry into politics.\n\n==Early life and career==\nOuellette was born and raised in [[Calgary]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ouellette|first1=Robert-Falcon|title=Introducing Robert Falcon Ouellette|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D-BL4sB9zNY|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=March 25, 2016|date=June 6, 2014}}</ref> His [[namesake]] was his mother's younger brother Robert-Falcon Green<ref>{{cite web|url=http://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QV7C-LCWS|title=England and Wales Birth Registration Index, 1837-2008|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|website=[[FamilySearch]]|access-date=September 21, 2016}}</ref> who died in 1961 at age 9.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QVCG-BRWH|title=England and Wales Death Registration Index 1837-2007|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|website=[[FamilySearch]]|access-date=September 21, 2016}}</ref> His mother was born in [[Tottenham]], [[north London|North]] [[London]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QVQ1-BFF5|title=England and Wales Birth Registration Index, 1837-2008|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|website=[[FamilySearch]]|access-date=September 21, 2016}}</ref> and moved from [[England]] to Canada in 1974 and his father was mix of [[Cree]] and [[M\u00e9tis in Canada|M\u00e9tis]]<ref>{{Cite news|title=Liberal MP: For reconciliation to happen, department needs to go|url=http://www.hilltimes.com/2016/12/16/liberal-mp-wants-hold-government-account-undrip/91345|newspaper=[[The Hill Times]]|last=Nash|first=Chelsea|date=December 14, 2016|access-date=December 17, 2016|quote=''Mr. Ouellette\u2019s father was a mix of Cree and M\u00e9tis.''}}</ref> and from the [[Red Pheasant First Nation]], located south of [[North Battleford|North Battleford, Saskatchewan]].<ref name=\"HuffingtonPost Winnipeg Centre 2015\" /> Ouellette was raised primarily by his mother, a poorly educated woman with a history of depression.<ref name=\"HuffingtonPost Winnipeg Centre 2015\" /> Ouellette's father was a student in the [[Canadian Indian residential school system]] and an alcoholic who was sometimes absent.<ref name=\"HuffingtonPost Winnipeg Centre 2015\" />\n\nOuellette grew up in poor conditions, often going hungry, and he once spent a summer homeless in Winnipeg.<ref name=\"HuffingtonPost Winnipeg Centre 2015\" />  Determined to change her son's future, Ouellette's mother insisted that he take the admissions test for the [[Strathcona-Tweedsmuir School]], an elite private school.<ref name=\"HuffingtonPost Winnipeg Centre 2015\" /> After Ouellette was admitted, his mother paid for his tuition by taking out a loan she could not afford to pay back.<ref name=\"HuffingtonPost Winnipeg Centre 2015\">{{cite web | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2015/09/19/winnipeg-centre-pat-martin-robert-falcon-ouellette-_n_8164126.html | title=Winnipeg Centre: Pat Martin, Robert-Falcon Ouellette Make Riding Key NDP-Liberal Battle | publisher=[[Huffington Post Canada]] | date=20 September 2015 | accessdate=26 October 2015 | author=Raj, Althia}}</ref><ref name=\"WFP Profile\" />\n\nOuellette earned a bachelor of arts in music from the [[University of Calgary]], a master's in music and a master's in education from [[Laval University]], and a [[doctorate|PhD]] in anthropology, also from Laval.<ref name=\"WFP Profile\">{{cite web | url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/special/civicelection2014/mayor/the-most-interesting-man-in-the-game-279654562.html | title=The Most Interesting Man in the Game | publisher=[[Winnipeg Free Press]] | date=18 October 2014 | accessdate=26 October 2015 | author=Welch, Mary Agnes}}</ref>\n\nHe retired from the [[Royal Canadian Navy]] after nearly two decades of service with the rank of [[Petty officer, 2nd class|Petty Officer 2nd class]] and remains as part of the [[Primary Reserve#Naval Reserve|Naval Reserve]].  He moved to Winnipeg in 2011 from [[Quebec City]] after he was appointed as director of Aboriginal Focus Programs at the [[University of Manitoba]].\n\n==Municipal politics==\nIn 2005, Ouelette ran for a council seat for [[Quebec City]] [[Quebec City Council|Council]], but lost by 170 votes.<ref name=\"WFP Profile\" />\n\nOuellette finished third in the [[2014 Manitoba municipal elections#Winnipeg|2014 Winnipeg mayoral election]].<ref name=\"Indigenous university\" /> He had run on a platform of dedicated infrastructure funding and campaign finance reform. Shortly after his defeat, he declared that he was developing a business plan to open a Winnipeg university catering to indigenous post-secondary students.<ref name=\"Indigenous university\">{{cite web | url=http://www.themanitoban.com/2014/12/robert-falcon-ouellette-wants-indigenous-university/21850/ | title=Robert-Falcon Ouellette Wants Indigenous University | publisher=[[The Manitoban]] | date=3 December 2014 | accessdate=26 October 2015 | author=Hatherly, Dana}}</ref>\n\n==Federal politics==\nIn the [[2015 Canadian federal election|2015 election]], Ouellette took over 50% of the vote and defeated longtime NDP MP [[Pat Martin]] in [[Winnipeg Centre]]. Ouellette resigned his position with the University of Manitoba in July 2015 to focus on his campaign.<ref name=\"Winnipeg's amazing race\">{{cite web | url=http://www.macleans.ca/politics/ottawa/winnipegs-amazing-race/ | title=Winnipeg\u2019s amazing race | publisher=[[Maclean's]] | date=24 September 2015 | accessdate=26 October 2015 | author=Macdonald, Nancy}}</ref> After his election, Ouellette was considered a leading candidate for the position of [[Minister of Aboriginal Affairs and Northern Development|Minister of Aboriginal Affairs]].<ref name=\"Aboriginal affairs\">{{cite web | url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/indigenous-mps-aboriginal-affairs-cabinet-justin-trudeau-1.3285509 | title=Justin Trudeau has strong slate of aboriginal MPs when considering cabinet | publisher=[[CBC News]] | date=24 October 2015 | accessdate=26 October 2015 | author=Roman, Karina}}</ref>\n\nOuellette withdrew from the race to be [[Speaker of the House of Commons (Canada)|Speaker of the House of Commons]] after making comments at a Winnipeg town hall meeting stating the position comes with \"great influence\" over the Prime Minister to the extent of calling the Prime Minister to the Speaker's Chair to address constituent's concerns.<ref name=\"Inappropriate remarks regarding role of Speaker of House of Commons\">{{cite web | url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/rookie-winnipeg-mp-withdraws-from-speaker-race-following-comments-at-meeting/article27521981/ | title=Rookie Winnipeg MP withdraws from Speaker race following comments at meeting | publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]] | date=29 November 2015 | accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe was the only Liberal MP to have voted against the bill that legalized euthanasia, saying it was against his deep spiritual beliefs.<ref>[http://aptnnews.ca/2016/04/20/indigenous-liberal-mp-ouellette-voting-against-governments-assisted-dying-bill/ Indigenous Liberal MP Ouellette voting against government assisted dying bill, 20 April 2016]</ref> He voted in support Nathaniel Erskine-Smith's Bill C-246: An Act to amend the Criminal Code, the Fisheries Act, the Textile Labelling Act, the Wild Animal and Plant Protection and Regulation of International and Interprovincial Trade Act and the Canada Consumer Product Safety Act (animal protection).<ref>[https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2016/10/06/nathaniel-erskine-smith-animal-cruelty-bill-c-246_n_12371614.html/ Nathaniel Erskine-Smith's Animal Cruelty Bill Defeated, 6 October 2016]</ref> Ouellette also voted against the bill that ordered striking Canada Post staff back to work for supporting employees in Canada Post dispute.<ref>[https://www.winnipegfreepress.com/local/winnipeg-liberal-mps-side-with-employees-in-canada-post-dispute-501283731.html / Winnipeg Liberal MPs side with employees in Canada Post dispute, 26 November 2018]</ref> Ouellette is one of the MPs who break ranks most often still toe the party line more than 87% of the time.<ref>[https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/grenier-party-line-voting-1.3984516/ Liberal backbenchers, Tory leadership hopefuls among Parliament's biggest dissenters, 21 February 2017]</ref>\n\nOuellette was the chair of Indigenous Caucus and the member of Standing Committee on Health and Finance. He is also the co-chair of All-Party Parliamentary Group (APPG) to end Slavery and Human Trafficking.<ref>[https://arpacanada.ca/news/2018/05/10/anti-porn-mp-selected-to-co-chair-human-trafficking-parliamentary-group/ ANTI-PORN MP SELECTED TO CO-CHAIR HUMAN TRAFFICKING PARLIAMENTARY GROUP, 10 May 2018]</ref> He is a supporter of the Moose Hide Campaign which is aimed to fight against violence towards women and children and human trafficking in\u00a0Canada.<ref>[https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2017/05/05/robert-falcon-ouellette-cree-house-commons_n_16434722.html/ Robert-Falcon Ouellette Delivers Speech In Cree To Ask For Help Protecting Indigenous Women, 5 May 2017]</ref>\n\nSince elected in 2015, Ouellette started to fight for rights of indigenous languages. On May 4, 2017, Ouellette gave the first entire speech in an indigenous language (Cree) in the House of Commons about violence and missing and murdered indigenous women and girls, and asked the House of Commons to offer translation services.<ref>[https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/house-looking-into-indigenous-interpretation-in-the-commons-1.3721747/ House looking into Indigenous interpretation in the Commons, 14 December 2017]</ref><ref>[https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/indigenous-cree-ojibwe-commons-robert-falcon-ouellette-geoff-regan-speaker-interpretation-1.4437190/ House of Commons gearing up for Indigenous languages in chamber, 11 December 2017]</ref><ref>[https://www.hilltimes.com/2018/12/03/indigenous-languages-matter-mp-falcon-ouellete-dreams-day-house-debates-translated-native-tongue/178898/ Indigenous languages matter: MP Falcon-Ouellete dreams of day when House debates are translated in his native tongue, 3 February 2018]</ref><ref>[https://www.winnipegfreepress.com/local/this-is-it-for-indigenous-languages-manitoba-mp-says-in-funding-plea-478008473.html/ 'This is it for Indigenous languages,' Manitoba MP says in funding plea, 27 March 2018]</ref> The House of Commons adopted changes to provide for the simultaneous interpretation of Indigenous languages during proceedings late in 2018.<ref>[https://ici.radio-canada.ca/espaces-autochtones/1140002/langues-autochtones-traduction-chambre-communes-ottawa-robert-falcon-ouellette/ Les langues autochtones maintenant bienvenues aux Communes, 5 December 2018]</ref><ref>[https://www.hilltimes.com/2019/01/28/changes-provide-indigenous-language-interpretation-house-symbolic-important-youth-says-liberal-mp-ouellette/185355/ This is something I\u2019ve been fighting for now for two years almost, Indigenous language interpretation in the House important symbol for youth, says Liberal MP Ouellette, 28 January 2019]</ref> On January 28, 2019 Ouellette became the first MP to speak in an indigenous language while the House provided live translation.<ref>[https://www.hilltimes.com/2019/02/06/helping-make-house-history-meet-cree-translator-kevin-lewis/187072/ Helping make House history: meet Cree translator Kevin Lewis, 6 February 2019]</ref><ref>[https://www.winnipegfreepress.com/local/ouellette-interpreter-bring-cree-voice-to-house-of-commons-504990672.html/ Ouellette, interpreter bring Cree voice to House of Commons, 28 January 2019]</ref><ref>[https://globalnews.ca/news/4901314/indigenous-winnipeg-mp-delivers-historic-speech-in-house-of-commons/ Indigenous Winnipeg MP delivers speech in Cree in House of Commons, 29 January 2019]</ref>\n\nOuellette has been working on the historic Child & Family Welfare Law since 2015.<ref>[https://aptnnews.ca/2019/05/09/we-cannot-have-canadas-commitment-die-on-the-order-paper-mps-hear-the-last-arguments-for-and-against-the-child-welfare-legislation/ MPs hear the last arguments for and against the child welfare legislation, 9 May 2019]</ref>  The legislation, Bill C-92, would ensure that Indigenous government jurisdiction on this matter over rides other levels of government including provincial and federal. This is permitted under section 92(24) of the Constitution. This bill was co-developed with Indigenous partners, including the Assembly of First Nations, Inuit Tapiriit Kanatami, and the Metis National Council, Bill C-92 seeks to affirm Indigenous peoples\u2019 inherent right to exercise jurisdiction over child and family services. Indigenous peoples should be allowed to care for their own children in a culturally appropriate way. For over 20 years in Manitoba, NDP and Conservative governments took more children into the child welfare system than at any point during the height of the Indian Residential School era. The Federal Child Welfare Reform legislation (C-92) has passed and will come into force in its entirety on January 1, 2020.\n\nSince 2016, Ouellette started to work with Lillian Dyck for a new law<ref>[https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/robert-falcon-ouellette-bill-mmiw-1.4103247/ Manitoba MP stands behind bill aimed at deterring violence against Indigenous women, 6 May 2017]</ref> which would help protect Indigenous women if they were victims of violent crime.<ref>[https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/robert-falcon-ouellette-bill-mmiw-1.4103247/ People who kill Indigenous women punished less than those who kill non-Indigenous women, Senator\u2019s study finds, 28 November 2018]</ref> The vote was lost and the bill defeated during second reading in the House of Commons in April 2019.\n\nIn May 2016, Ouellete introduced his first Private Member's Bill C-318: National Residential School Memorial Day to Parliament.<ref>[https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/robert-falcon-ouellette-private-members-bill-residential-school-system-1.3572130/ Robert-Falcon Ouellette to introduce bill for national residential school memorial day, 7 May 2016]</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, Ouellette sponsored Dougald Lamont's petition (from Winnipeg, Manitoba): E-211 (SOCIAL BENEFITS) to call upon the Minister of Finance to join with interested Provinces, Municipalities and Indigenous communities to fund and launch experimental pilot Mincome projects, as soon as possible, in order to determine the efficacy and viability of a Guaranteed Minimum Income in Canada, and to include funding for these projects in the 2016-2017 budget.\n\nIn July 2016, Ouellette sponsored Collin Bryce Theo Kennedy's petition: E-492 (TRANSPORTATION) to call upon the Minister of Health to and Minister of Transportation to request enforcement of the Canada Health Act to:\n1. Ensure there is adequate cost-free parking for patients and caregivers in and around medical facilities; and\n2. Where metered parking is not to be removed, that there is a means to identify those who are utilizing the parking space in order to gain access to medical facilities without cost to the patient; their family or caregivers regardless of the duration.<ref>[https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/cancer-patient-parking-meter-dies-1.4943249/ Cancer patient who filled Winnipeg meter with spray foam to protest hospital parking fees dies, 12 December 2018]</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, Ouellette sponsored Jeff Ward's petition(from Victoria, British Columbia): E-607 (NATIONAL HOLIDAYS) to call upon the House of Commons to designate June 21 of each year as a legal holiday to be kept and observed throughout Canada. This day should serve to create and strengthen opportunities for Reconciliation and cultural exchange among Canadians. The day should facilitate connections between Indigenous and non-Indigenous Canadians in positive and meaningful ways. This day should solidify the original intent of National Aboriginal Day as a day for Canadians to recognize and celebrate the unique heritage, diverse cultures and outstanding contributions of First Nations, Inuit and M\u00e9tis peoples.\n\nIn September 2017, Ouellette sponsored Jodene McNarland's petition(from Winnipeg, Manitoba): E-1234 (OFFICIAL LANGUAGES OF CANADA) to call upon the House of Commons to provide interpretation and translation services in Nehiyawewin/Cree in the House of Commons.\n\nIn October 2018, Ouellette sponsored Renate Schulz's petition(from Winnipeg, Manitoba):E-1866 (FIREARMS) to call upon the Government of Canada to draft legislation immediately in order to ban handguns and military-style assault weapons in Canada.\n\nIn December 2018, Ouellette sponsored Randolph Shrofel's petition(from Sandy Hook, Manitoba): E-1961 (CANADIAN HERITAGE) to call upon the Government of Canada to revise the Coat of Arms of Canada to include representation of the Indigenous peoples of Canada.<ref>[https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2019/01/18/canada-coat-of-arms-indigenous_a_23646616/ Canada\u2019s Coat Of Arms Needs Redesign To Include Indigenous Peoples: Petition, 20 January 2019]</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Ouellette sponsored Renae Shingoose's petition(from Saskatoon, Saskatchewan): E-2160 (SENTENCES IN THE CRIMINAL CODE) to call upon the House of Commons to appeal and revise the decision of Bill S-215 to where treatment and rehabilitation is mandatory for all violent offenders of Aboriginal women.\n\nIn June 2019, Ouellette sponsored Yasir Naqvi's petition (from Toronto, Ontario): E-2240 (CANADIAN CITIZENSHIP) to call upon the House of Commons to cooperate and Pass Bill C-99 to update Canada's Oath of Citizenship to respect and recognize Indigenous rights before the House rises on June 21, 2019.\n\nIn September 2018, to raise awareness about the violence and drug addiction issues facing Winnipeg and get the provincial and city government's actions, Ouellette erected a tipi in Central Park, a no-go zone in Winnipeg, and slept out in the open for a few days.<ref>[https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/central-park-sleepout-robert-falcon-oullette-1.4812534/ MP Robert-Falcon Ouellette sleeps in Winnipeg's Central Park in response to spike in crime, 6 September 2018]</ref> Then he worked with Doug Eyolfson to provide a substantive House of Commons Health Committee Report on meth & addiction.<ref>[https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/manitoba-meth-ottawa-hearing-1.4926739/ Manitoba meth crisis under the microscope at federal committee hearing, 29 November 2018]</ref> He also called on all MPs to combat meth crisis in November 2018.<ref>[https://www.hilltimes.com/2018/11/19/winnipeg-liberal-mp-ouellette-solicited-sex-exchange-money-constituency-office-two-young-meth-addicted-women-calls-mps-work-together-fight/176443/ Winnipeg Liberal MP Ouellette calls on all MPs to combat meth crisis, 19 November 2018]</ref>\n\nHe was defeated in the [[2019 Canadian federal election|2019 election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.winnipegfreepress.com/special/federal-election/gazan-ousts-ouellette-to-return-riding-to-ndp-563602082.html|title=Gazan ousts Ouellette to return riding to NDP|publisher=Winnipeg Free Press|date=21 October 2019| accessdate=22 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOuellette lives in the inner city of [[West Broadway, Winnipeg]].<ref>[https://robertfalcon.ca/about/ RobertFalcon.ca | About]</ref>\n\n==Electoral record==\n{{Canadian election result/top|CA|2019|Winnipeg Centre|percent=yes|change=yes|expenditures=yes}}\n{{CANelec|CA|NDP|[[Leah Gazan]]|13,073|41.2|+13.2|\u2013}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Liberal|Robert-Falcon Ouellette|10,704|33.7|-20.8|\u2013}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Conservative|Ryan Dyck|5,561|17.5|+5.1|\u2013}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Green|Andrea Shalay|1,661|5.2|+1.1|\u2013}}\n{{CANelec|CA|PPC|Yogi Henderson|474|1.5|\u2013|\u2013}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Christian Heritage|Stephanie Hein|251|0.8|+0.1|\u2013}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total valid votes/Expense limit|31,724|100.0 &nbsp;|| }}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total rejected ballots|274||}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Turnout|31,998|54.2|}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Eligible voters|59,012}}\n{{CANelec/gain|CA|NDP|Liberal|+17.0}}\n{{CANelec/source|Source: [[Elections Canada]]<ref>{{cite web |title=List of confirmed candidates |url=https://www.elections.ca/content2.aspx?section=can&dir=cand/lst&document=index&lang=e |website=Elections Canada |accessdate=October 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Election Night Results |url=https://enr.elections.ca/ElectoralDistricts.aspx?lang=e |publisher=Elections Canada |accessdate=November 9, 2019}}</ref>}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Canadian election result/top|CA|2015|percent=yes|change=yes|expenditures=yes}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Liberal|Robert-Falcon Ouellette|18,471|54.51|+43.44|$78,690.24}}\n{{CANelec|CA|NDP|[[Pat Martin]]|9,490|28.01|\u221225.65|$107,665.59}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Conservative|Allie Szarkiewicz|4,189|12.36|\u221215.28|$32,494.32}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Green|Don Woodstock|1,379|4.07|\u22122.98|$38,782.49}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Christian Heritage|Scott Miller|221|0.65|n/a|$1,210.15}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Communist|[[Darrell Rankin]]|135|0.40|\u22120.19|$0.00}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total valid votes/Expense limit|33,885|100.00|&nbsp;|$191,132.58}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total rejected ballots|281|0.82|&ndash;}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Turnout|34,166|61.41|&ndash;}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Eligible voters|55,633}}\n{{CANelec/gain|CA|Liberal|NDP|+34.59}}\n{{CANelec/source|Source: [[Elections Canada]]<ref>[http://www.elections.ca/Scripts/vis/candidates?L=e&ED=46011&EV=41&EV_TYPE=1&PC=&PROV=MB&PROVID=46&MAPID=&QID=8&PAGEID=17&TPAGEID=&PD=&STAT_CODE_ID=-1 Elections Canada \u2013 Confirmed candidates for Winnipeg Centre, 30 September 2015]</ref><ref>[http://www.elections.ca/content2.aspx?section=can&dir=cand/canlim&document=index&lang=e Elections Canada \u2013 Preliminary Election Expenses Limits for Candidates]</ref><ref>http://www.elections.ca/WPAPPS/WPF/EN/CC/DistrictReport?act=C23&eventid=41&returntype=1&option=3&queryid=72c1eb8bd75a4964986c724956f5a358</ref>}}\n{{end}}\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"3\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ 2014 Winnipeg Mayoral\n|-\n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\" width=\"200px\" scope=\"col\" | Candidate\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\" width=\"50px\" scope=\"col\" | Votes\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\" width=\"50px\" scope=\"col\" | %\n|- style=\"text-align:left; background:#cfc;\"\n| scope=\"row\" |(x) [[Brian Bowman (politician)|Brian Bowman]] ||111,504 ||47.54\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |[[Judy Wasylycia-Leis]] ||58,440 ||24.29\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |Robert-Falcon Ouellette ||36,823 ||15.70\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |Gord Steeves ||21,080 ||8.99\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |David Sanders ||3,718 ||1.59\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |Paula Havixbeck ||2,083 ||0.89\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |Michel Fillion ||898 ||0.38\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://robertfalcon.ca/about/ Official bio]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ouellette, Robert-Falcon}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party of Canada MPs]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Canada from Manitoba]]\n[[Category:First Nations politicians]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Calgary]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Winnipeg]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of M\u00e9tis descent]]\n[[Category:Cree people]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of English descent]]\n[[Category:Indigenous Members of the House of Commons of Canada]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Navy officers]]\n[[Category:Canadian anthropologists]]\n[[Category:Universit\u00e9 Laval alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Calgary alumni]]\n[[Category:First Nations academics]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name             =Robert-Falcon Ouellette\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image            = \n| imagesize        = 200px\n| riding           = [[Winnipeg Centre]]\n| parliament       = Canadian\n| term_start       =October 19, 2015\n| term_end         = October 21, 2019\n| predecessor      =[[Pat Martin]]\n| successor        = [[Leah Gazan]]\n| birth_date       ={{birth date and age|1976|11|22}}\n| birth_place      =[[Calgary]], [[Alberta]], Canada\n| profession       = Anthropologist\n| party            = [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]]\n| residence        = [[Downtown Winnipeg|West Broadway, Winnipeg, Manitoba]]\n| footnotes        = \n| alma_mater       = [[Universit\u00e9 Laval]] <small>([[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]], [[Master of Arts|M.A.]])</small><br />[[University of Calgary]] <small>([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]])</small>\n| education        = Doctor of Philosophy, Anthropology\n<!--Military service-->\n| allegiance         = [[Canadian Forces]]\n| branch             = [[Royal Canadian Navy]]\n| rank               = Petty Officer 1st class\n| unit               = [[HMCS Chippawa]]\n| serviceyears       = 1992-present\n|}}\n'''Robert-Falcon Ouellette''' (born November 22, 1976) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] politician, who also goes by the initials of RFO or simply called The Falcon, who represented the [[electoral district (Canada)|riding]] of [[Winnipeg Centre]] in the [[House of Commons of Canada]] for one term. He was previously a candidate for [[Mayor of Winnipeg]] in the [[2014 Manitoba municipal elections|2014 municipal election]], finishing third.\n\nOf mixed [[French Canadian|French]] and Cree descent, Ouellette was a veteran of nearly twenty years in the [[Canadian Forces]] and a university professor before his entry into politics.\n\n==Early life and career==\nOuellette was born and raised in [[Calgary]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ouellette|first1=Robert-Falcon|title=Introducing Robert Falcon Ouellette|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D-BL4sB9zNY|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=March 25, 2016|date=June 6, 2014}}</ref> His [[namesake]] was his mother's younger brother Robert-Falcon Green<ref>{{cite web|url=http://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QV7C-LCWS|title=England and Wales Birth Registration Index, 1837-2008|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|website=[[FamilySearch]]|access-date=September 21, 2016}}</ref> who died in 1961 at age 9.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QVCG-BRWH|title=England and Wales Death Registration Index 1837-2007|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|website=[[FamilySearch]]|access-date=September 21, 2016}}</ref> His mother was born in [[Tottenham]], [[north London|North]] [[London]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QVQ1-BFF5|title=England and Wales Birth Registration Index, 1837-2008|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|website=[[FamilySearch]]|access-date=September 21, 2016}}</ref> and moved from [[England]] to Canada in 1974 and his father was mix of [[Cree]] and [[M\u00e9tis in Canada|M\u00e9tis]]<ref>{{Cite news|title=Liberal MP: For reconciliation to happen, department needs to go|url=http://www.hilltimes.com/2016/12/16/liberal-mp-wants-hold-government-account-undrip/91345|newspaper=[[The Hill Times]]|last=Nash|first=Chelsea|date=December 14, 2016|access-date=December 17, 2016|quote=''Mr. Ouellette\u2019s father was a mix of Cree and M\u00e9tis.''}}</ref> and from the [[Red Pheasant First Nation]], located south of [[North Battleford|North Battleford, Saskatchewan]].<ref name=\"HuffingtonPost Winnipeg Centre 2015\" /> Ouellette was raised primarily by his mother, a poorly educated woman with a history of depression.<ref name=\"HuffingtonPost Winnipeg Centre 2015\" /> Ouellette's father was a student in the [[Canadian Indian residential school system]] and an alcoholic who was sometimes absent.<ref name=\"HuffingtonPost Winnipeg Centre 2015\" />\n\nOuellette grew up in poor conditions, often going hungry, and he once spent a summer homeless in Winnipeg.<ref name=\"HuffingtonPost Winnipeg Centre 2015\" />  Determined to change her son's future, Ouellette's mother insisted that he take the admissions test for the [[Strathcona-Tweedsmuir School]], an elite private school.<ref name=\"HuffingtonPost Winnipeg Centre 2015\" /> After Ouellette was admitted, his mother paid for his tuition by taking out a loan she could not afford to pay back.<ref name=\"HuffingtonPost Winnipeg Centre 2015\">{{cite web | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2015/09/19/winnipeg-centre-pat-martin-robert-falcon-ouellette-_n_8164126.html | title=Winnipeg Centre: Pat Martin, Robert-Falcon Ouellette Make Riding Key NDP-Liberal Battle | publisher=[[Huffington Post Canada]] | date=20 September 2015 | accessdate=26 October 2015 | author=Raj, Althia}}</ref><ref name=\"WFP Profile\" />\n\nOuellette earned a bachelor of arts in music from the [[University of Calgary]], a master's in music and a master's in education from [[Laval University]], and a [[doctorate|PhD]] in anthropology, also from Laval.<ref name=\"WFP Profile\">{{cite web | url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/special/civicelection2014/mayor/the-most-interesting-man-in-the-game-279654562.html | title=The Most Interesting Man in the Game | publisher=[[Winnipeg Free Press]] | date=18 October 2014 | accessdate=26 October 2015 | author=Welch, Mary Agnes}}</ref>\n\nHe retired from the [[Royal Canadian Navy]] after nearly two decades of service with the rank of [[Petty officer, 2nd class|Petty Officer 2nd class]] and remains as part of the [[Primary Reserve#Naval Reserve|Naval Reserve]].  He moved to Winnipeg in 2011 from [[Quebec City]] after he was appointed as director of Aboriginal Focus Programs at the [[University of Manitoba]].\n\n==Municipal politics==\nIn 2005, Ouelette ran for a council seat for [[Quebec City]] [[Quebec City Council|Council]], but lost by 170 votes.<ref name=\"WFP Profile\" />\n\nOuellette finished third in the [[2014 Manitoba municipal elections#Winnipeg|2014 Winnipeg mayoral election]].<ref name=\"Indigenous university\" /> He had run on a platform of dedicated infrastructure funding and campaign finance reform. Shortly after his defeat, he declared that he was developing a business plan to open a Winnipeg university catering to indigenous post-secondary students.<ref name=\"Indigenous university\">{{cite web | url=http://www.themanitoban.com/2014/12/robert-falcon-ouellette-wants-indigenous-university/21850/ | title=Robert-Falcon Ouellette Wants Indigenous University | publisher=[[The Manitoban]] | date=3 December 2014 | accessdate=26 October 2015 | author=Hatherly, Dana}}</ref>\n\n==Federal politics==\nIn the [[2015 Canadian federal election|2015 election]], Ouellette took over 50% of the vote and defeated longtime NDP MP [[Pat Martin]] in [[Winnipeg Centre]]. Ouellette resigned his position with the University of Manitoba in July 2015 to focus on his campaign.<ref name=\"Winnipeg's amazing race\">{{cite web | url=http://www.macleans.ca/politics/ottawa/winnipegs-amazing-race/ | title=Winnipeg\u2019s amazing race | publisher=[[Maclean's]] | date=24 September 2015 | accessdate=26 October 2015 | author=Macdonald, Nancy}}</ref> After his election, Ouellette was considered a leading candidate for the position of [[Minister of Aboriginal Affairs and Northern Development|Minister of Aboriginal Affairs]].<ref name=\"Aboriginal affairs\">{{cite web | url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/indigenous-mps-aboriginal-affairs-cabinet-justin-trudeau-1.3285509 | title=Justin Trudeau has strong slate of aboriginal MPs when considering cabinet | publisher=[[CBC News]] | date=24 October 2015 | accessdate=26 October 2015 | author=Roman, Karina}}</ref>\n\nOuellette withdrew from the race to be [[Speaker of the House of Commons (Canada)|Speaker of the House of Commons]] after making comments at a Winnipeg town hall meeting stating the position comes with \"great influence\" over the Prime Minister to the extent of calling the Prime Minister to the Speaker's Chair to address constituent's concerns.<ref name=\"Inappropriate remarks regarding role of Speaker of House of Commons\">{{cite web | url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/rookie-winnipeg-mp-withdraws-from-speaker-race-following-comments-at-meeting/article27521981/ | title=Rookie Winnipeg MP withdraws from Speaker race following comments at meeting | publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]] | date=29 November 2015 | accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe was the only Liberal MP to have voted against the bill that legalized euthanasia, saying it was against his deep spiritual beliefs.<ref>[http://aptnnews.ca/2016/04/20/indigenous-liberal-mp-ouellette-voting-against-governments-assisted-dying-bill/ Indigenous Liberal MP Ouellette voting against government assisted dying bill, 20 April 2016]</ref> He voted in support Nathaniel Erskine-Smith\u2019s Bill C-246: An Act to amend the Criminal Code, the Fisheries Act, the Textile Labelling Act, the Wild Animal and Plant Protection and Regulation of International and Interprovincial Trade Act and the Canada Consumer Product Safety Act (animal protection).<ref>[https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2016/10/06/nathaniel-erskine-smith-animal-cruelty-bill-c-246_n_12371614.html/ Nathaniel Erskine-Smith's Animal Cruelty Bill Defeated, 6 October 2016]</ref> Ouellette also voted against the bill that ordered striking Canada Post staff back to work for supporting employees in Canada Post dispute.<ref>[https://www.winnipegfreepress.com/local/winnipeg-liberal-mps-side-with-employees-in-canada-post-dispute-501283731.html / Winnipeg Liberal MPs side with employees in Canada Post dispute, 26 November 2018]</ref> Ouellette is one of the MPs who break ranks most often still toe the party line more than 87% of the time.<ref>[https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/grenier-party-line-voting-1.3984516/ Liberal backbenchers, Tory leadership hopefuls among Parliament's biggest dissenters, 21 February 2017]</ref>\n\nOuellette was the chair of Indigenous Caucus and the member of Standing Committee on Health and Finance. He is also the co-chair of All-Party Parliamentary Group (APPG) to end Slavery and Human Trafficking.<ref>[https://arpacanada.ca/news/2018/05/10/anti-porn-mp-selected-to-co-chair-human-trafficking-parliamentary-group/ ANTI-PORN MP SELECTED TO CO-CHAIR HUMAN TRAFFICKING PARLIAMENTARY GROUP, 10 May 2018]</ref> He is a supporter of the Moose Hide Campaign which is aimed to fight against violence towards women and children and human trafficking in\u00a0Canada.<ref>[https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2017/05/05/robert-falcon-ouellette-cree-house-commons_n_16434722.html/ Robert-Falcon Ouellette Delivers Speech In Cree To Ask For Help Protecting Indigenous Women, 5 May 2017]</ref>\n\nSince elected in 2015, Ouellette started to fight for rights of indigenous languages. On May 4, 2017, Ouellette gave the first entire speech in an indigenous language (Cree) in the House of Commons about violence and missing and murdered indigenous women and girls, and asked the House of Commons to offer translation services.<ref>[https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/house-looking-into-indigenous-interpretation-in-the-commons-1.3721747/ House looking into Indigenous interpretation in the Commons, 14 December 2017]</ref><ref>[https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/indigenous-cree-ojibwe-commons-robert-falcon-ouellette-geoff-regan-speaker-interpretation-1.4437190/ House of Commons gearing up for Indigenous languages in chamber, 11 December 2017]</ref><ref>[https://www.hilltimes.com/2018/12/03/indigenous-languages-matter-mp-falcon-ouellete-dreams-day-house-debates-translated-native-tongue/178898/ Indigenous languages matter: MP Falcon-Ouellete dreams of day when House debates are translated in his native tongue, 3 February 2018]</ref><ref>[https://www.winnipegfreepress.com/local/this-is-it-for-indigenous-languages-manitoba-mp-says-in-funding-plea-478008473.html/ 'This is it for Indigenous languages,' Manitoba MP says in funding plea, 27 March 2018]</ref> The House of Commons adopted changes to provide for the simultaneous interpretation of Indigenous languages during proceedings late in 2018.<ref>[https://ici.radio-canada.ca/espaces-autochtones/1140002/langues-autochtones-traduction-chambre-communes-ottawa-robert-falcon-ouellette/ Les langues autochtones maintenant bienvenues aux Communes, 5 December 2018]</ref><ref>[https://www.hilltimes.com/2019/01/28/changes-provide-indigenous-language-interpretation-house-symbolic-important-youth-says-liberal-mp-ouellette/185355/ This is something I\u2019ve been fighting for now for two years almost, Indigenous language interpretation in the House important symbol for youth, says Liberal MP Ouellette, 28 January 2019]</ref> On January 28, 2019 Ouellette became the first MP to speak in an indigenous language while the House provided live translation.<ref>[https://www.hilltimes.com/2019/02/06/helping-make-house-history-meet-cree-translator-kevin-lewis/187072/ Helping make House history: meet Cree translator Kevin Lewis, 6 February 2019]</ref><ref>[https://www.winnipegfreepress.com/local/ouellette-interpreter-bring-cree-voice-to-house-of-commons-504990672.html/ Ouellette, interpreter bring Cree voice to House of Commons, 28 January 2019]</ref><ref>[https://globalnews.ca/news/4901314/indigenous-winnipeg-mp-delivers-historic-speech-in-house-of-commons/ Indigenous Winnipeg MP delivers speech in Cree in House of Commons, 29 January 2019]</ref>\n\nOuellette has been working on the historic Child & Family Welfare Law since 2015.<ref>[https://aptnnews.ca/2019/05/09/we-cannot-have-canadas-commitment-die-on-the-order-paper-mps-hear-the-last-arguments-for-and-against-the-child-welfare-legislation/ MPs hear the last arguments for and against the child welfare legislation, 9 May 2019]</ref>  The legislation, Bill C-92, would ensure that Indigenous government jurisdiction on this matter over rides other levels of government including provincial and federal. This is permitted under section 92(24) of the Constitution. This bill was co-developed with Indigenous partners, including the Assembly of First Nations, Inuit Tapiriit Kanatami, and the Metis National Council, Bill C-92 seeks to affirm Indigenous peoples\u2019 inherent right to exercise jurisdiction over child and family services. Indigenous peoples should be allowed to care for their own children in a culturally appropriate way. For over 20 years in Manitoba, NDP and Conservative governments took more children into the child welfare system than at any point during the height of the Indian Residential School era. The Federal Child Welfare Reform legislation (C-92) has passed and will come into force in its entirety on January 1, 2020.\n\nSince 2016, Ouellette started to work with Lillian Dyck for a new law<ref>[https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/robert-falcon-ouellette-bill-mmiw-1.4103247/ Manitoba MP stands behind bill aimed at deterring violence against Indigenous women, 6 May 2017]</ref> which would help protect Indigenous women if they were victims of violent crime.<ref>[https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/robert-falcon-ouellette-bill-mmiw-1.4103247/ People who kill Indigenous women punished less than those who kill non-Indigenous women, Senator\u2019s study finds, 28 November 2018]</ref> The vote was lost and the bill defeated during second reading in the House of Commons in April 2019.\n\nIn May 2016, Ouellete introduced his first Private Member's Bill C-318: National Residential School Memorial Day to Parliament.<ref>[https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/robert-falcon-ouellette-private-members-bill-residential-school-system-1.3572130/ Robert-Falcon Ouellette to introduce bill for national residential school memorial day, 7 May 2016]</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, Ouellette sponsored Dougald Lamont's petition (from Winnipeg, Manitoba): E-211 (SOCIAL BENEFITS) to call upon the Minister of Finance to join with interested Provinces, Municipalities and Indigenous communities to fund and launch experimental pilot Mincome projects, as soon as possible, in order to determine the efficacy and viability of a Guaranteed Minimum Income in Canada, and to include funding for these projects in the 2016-2017 budget.\n\nIn July 2016, Ouellette sponsored Collin Bryce Theo Kennedy's petition: E-492 (TRANSPORTATION) to call upon the Minister of Health to and Minister of Transportation to request enforcement of the Canada Health Act to:\n1. Ensure there is adequate cost-free parking for patients and caregivers in and around medical facilities; and\n2. Where metered parking is not to be removed, that there is a means to identify those who are utilizing the parking space in order to gain access to medical facilities without cost to the patient; their family or caregivers regardless of the duration.<ref>[https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/cancer-patient-parking-meter-dies-1.4943249/ Cancer patient who filled Winnipeg meter with spray foam to protest hospital parking fees dies, 12 December 2018]</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, Ouellette sponsored Jeff Ward's petition(from Victoria, British Columbia): E-607 (NATIONAL HOLIDAYS) to call upon the House of Commons to designate June 21 of each year as a legal holiday to be kept and observed throughout Canada. This day should serve to create and strengthen opportunities for Reconciliation and cultural exchange among Canadians. The day should facilitate connections between Indigenous and non-Indigenous Canadians in positive and meaningful ways. This day should solidify the original intent of National Aboriginal Day as a day for Canadians to recognize and celebrate the unique heritage, diverse cultures and outstanding contributions of First Nations, Inuit and M\u00e9tis peoples.\n\nIn September 2017, Ouellette sponsored Jodene McNarland's petition(from Winnipeg, Manitoba): E-1234 (OFFICIAL LANGUAGES OF CANADA) to call upon the House of Commons to provide interpretation and translation services in Nehiyawewin/Cree in the House of Commons.\n\nIn October 2018, Ouellette sponsored Renate Schulz's petition(from Winnipeg, Manitoba):E-1866 (FIREARMS) to call upon the Government of Canada to draft legislation immediately in order to ban handguns and military-style assault weapons in Canada.\n\nIn December 2018, Ouellette sponsored Randolph Shrofel's petition(from Sandy Hook, Manitoba): E-1961 (CANADIAN HERITAGE) to call upon the Government of Canada to revise the Coat of Arms of Canada to include representation of the Indigenous peoples of Canada.<ref>[https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2019/01/18/canada-coat-of-arms-indigenous_a_23646616/ Canada\u2019s Coat Of Arms Needs Redesign To Include Indigenous Peoples: Petition, 20 January 2019]</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Ouellette sponsored Renae Shingoose's petition(from Saskatoon, Saskatchewan): E-2160 (SENTENCES IN THE CRIMINAL CODE) to call upon the House of Commons to appeal and revise the decision of Bill S-215 to where treatment and rehabilitation is mandatory for all violent offenders of Aboriginal women.\n\nIn June 2019, Ouellette sponsored Yasir Naqvi's petition (from Toronto, Ontario): E-2240 (CANADIAN CITIZENSHIP) to call upon the House of Commons to cooperate and Pass Bill C-99 to update Canada\u2019s Oath of Citizenship to respect and recognize Indigenous rights before the House rises on June 21, 2019.\n\nIn September 2018, to raise awareness about the violence and drug addiction issues facing Winnipeg and get the provincial and city government's actions, Ouellette erected a tipi in Central Park, a no-go zone in Winnipeg, and slept out in the open for a few days.<ref>[https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/central-park-sleepout-robert-falcon-oullette-1.4812534/ MP Robert-Falcon Ouellette sleeps in Winnipeg's Central Park in response to spike in crime, 6 September 2018]</ref> Then he worked with Doug Eyolfson to provide a substantive House of Commons Health Committee Report on meth & addiction.<ref>[https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/manitoba-meth-ottawa-hearing-1.4926739/ Manitoba meth crisis under the microscope at federal committee hearing, 29 November 2018]</ref> He also called on all MPs to combat meth crisis in November 2018.<ref>[https://www.hilltimes.com/2018/11/19/winnipeg-liberal-mp-ouellette-solicited-sex-exchange-money-constituency-office-two-young-meth-addicted-women-calls-mps-work-together-fight/176443/ Winnipeg Liberal MP Ouellette calls on all MPs to combat meth crisis, 19 November 2018]</ref>\n\nHe was defeated in the [[2019 Canadian federal election|2019 election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.winnipegfreepress.com/special/federal-election/gazan-ousts-ouellette-to-return-riding-to-ndp-563602082.html|title=Gazan ousts Ouellette to return riding to NDP|publisher=Winnipeg Free Press|date=21 October 2019| accessdate=22 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOuellette lives in the inner city of [[West Broadway, Winnipeg]].<ref>[https://robertfalcon.ca/about/ RobertFalcon.ca | About]</ref>\n\n==Electoral record==\n{{Canadian election result/top|CA|2019|Winnipeg Centre|percent=yes|change=yes|expenditures=yes}}\n{{CANelec|CA|NDP|[[Leah Gazan]]|13,073|41.2|+13.2|\u2013}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Liberal|Robert-Falcon Ouellette|10,704|33.7|-20.8|\u2013}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Conservative|Ryan Dyck|5,561|17.5|+5.1|\u2013}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Green|Andrea Shalay|1,661|5.2|+1.1|\u2013}}\n{{CANelec|CA|PPC|Yogi Henderson|474|1.5|\u2013|\u2013}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Christian Heritage|Stephanie Hein|251|0.8|+0.1|\u2013}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total valid votes/Expense limit|31,724|100.0 &nbsp;|| }}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total rejected ballots|274||}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Turnout|31,998|54.2|}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Eligible voters|59,012}}\n{{CANelec/gain|CA|NDP|Liberal|+17.0}}\n{{CANelec/source|Source: [[Elections Canada]]<ref>{{cite web |title=List of confirmed candidates |url=https://www.elections.ca/content2.aspx?section=can&dir=cand/lst&document=index&lang=e |website=Elections Canada |accessdate=October 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Election Night Results |url=https://enr.elections.ca/ElectoralDistricts.aspx?lang=e |publisher=Elections Canada |accessdate=November 9, 2019}}</ref>}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Canadian election result/top|CA|2015|percent=yes|change=yes|expenditures=yes}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Liberal|Robert-Falcon Ouellette|18,471|54.51|+43.44|$78,690.24}}\n{{CANelec|CA|NDP|[[Pat Martin]]|9,490|28.01|\u221225.65|$107,665.59}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Conservative|Allie Szarkiewicz|4,189|12.36|\u221215.28|$32,494.32}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Green|Don Woodstock|1,379|4.07|\u22122.98|$38,782.49}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Christian Heritage|Scott Miller|221|0.65|n/a|$1,210.15}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Communist|[[Darrell Rankin]]|135|0.40|\u22120.19|$0.00}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total valid votes/Expense limit|33,885|100.00|&nbsp;|$191,132.58}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total rejected ballots|281|0.82|&ndash;}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Turnout|34,166|61.41|&ndash;}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Eligible voters|55,633}}\n{{CANelec/gain|CA|Liberal|NDP|+34.59}}\n{{CANelec/source|Source: [[Elections Canada]]<ref>[http://www.elections.ca/Scripts/vis/candidates?L=e&ED=46011&EV=41&EV_TYPE=1&PC=&PROV=MB&PROVID=46&MAPID=&QID=8&PAGEID=17&TPAGEID=&PD=&STAT_CODE_ID=-1 Elections Canada \u2013 Confirmed candidates for Winnipeg Centre, 30 September 2015]</ref><ref>[http://www.elections.ca/content2.aspx?section=can&dir=cand/canlim&document=index&lang=e Elections Canada \u2013 Preliminary Election Expenses Limits for Candidates]</ref><ref>http://www.elections.ca/WPAPPS/WPF/EN/CC/DistrictReport?act=C23&eventid=41&returntype=1&option=3&queryid=72c1eb8bd75a4964986c724956f5a358</ref>}}\n{{end}}\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"3\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ 2014 Winnipeg Mayoral\n|-\n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\" width=\"200px\" scope=\"col\" | Candidate\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\" width=\"50px\" scope=\"col\" | Votes\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\" width=\"50px\" scope=\"col\" | %\n|- style=\"text-align:left; background:#cfc;\"\n| scope=\"row\" |(x) [[Brian Bowman (politician)|Brian Bowman]] ||111,504 ||47.54\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |[[Judy Wasylycia-Leis]] ||58,440 ||24.29\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |Robert-Falcon Ouellette ||36,823 ||15.70\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |Gord Steeves ||21,080 ||8.99\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |David Sanders ||3,718 ||1.59\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |Paula Havi