{"title_page": "Robert Woodard (baseball)", "text_new": "{{Infobox college coach\n| name               = Robert Woodard\n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| current_title      = [[Head coach]]\n| current_team       = [[Charlotte 49ers baseball|Charlotte]]\n| current_conference = [[Conference USA|C-USA]]\n| current_record     = 9\u20138\n| contract           = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1985|1|10}}\n| birth_place        = [[Winston-Salem, North Carolina]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| player_years1      = 2004\u20132007\n| player_team1       = [[North Carolina Tar Heels baseball|North Carolina]]\n| player_years2      = 2007\n| player_team2       = [[Eugene Emeralds]]\n| player_years3      = 2007\u20132008\n| player_team3       = [[Portland Beavers]]\n| player_years4      = 2008\n| player_team4       = [[Fort Wayne Wizards]]\n| player_years5      = 2008\u20132009\n| player_team5       = [[Lake Elsinore Storm]]\n| player_positions   = [[Pitcher]]\n| coach_years1       = 2010\u20132012\n| coach_team1        = North Carolina (asst)\n| coach_years2       = 2013\n| coach_team2        = [[UNC Wilmington Seahawks baseball|UNC Wilmington]] (asst)\n| coach_years3       = 2014\u20132016\n| coach_team3        = [[Virginia Tech Hokies baseball|Virginia Tech]] (asst)\n| coach_years4       = 2017\u20132019\n| coach_team4        = North Carolina (asst)\n| coach_years5       = 2020\u2013present\n| coach_team5        = [[Charlotte 49ers baseball|Charlotte]]\n| overall_record     = 9\u20138\n| tournament_record  = C-USA: 0\u20130<br>NCAA: 0\u20130\n| championships      = \n| awards             = \n| coaching_records   = \n| CBASEHOF_year      = \n}}\n\n'''Robert Suiter Woodard''' (born January 10, 1985) is an American baseball coach and former pitcher. He is the head baseball coach at the [[University of North Carolina at Charlotte]]. Woodard played [[college baseball]] at the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]] from 2004 to 2007 for coach [[Mike Fox (baseball)|Mike Fox]] and in [[Minor League Baseball]] (MiLB) for three seasons from 2007 to 2009.\n\nWoodard was born in [[Winston-Salem, North Carolina]]. He attended [[Myers Park High School]] in [[Charlotte, North Carolina]]. After graduation from high school, he decided to attend University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill to play baseball. After his junior season, he was selected by the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] in the [[2006 Major League Baseball draft]]'s 46th round. He returned to North Carolina for his senior season where he was drafted in the twentieth round of the [[2007 Major League Baseball draft]] by the [[San Diego Padres]].\n\nIn 2019, Woodard was named the head coach of the [[Charlotte 49ers baseball]] program.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/college/article232111957.html |title=Charlotte native and former UNC standout named 49ers baseball coach |author=David Scott |date=June 29, 2019 |publisher=Charlotte Observer |work=www.charlotteobserver.com |accessdate=July 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Amateur career==\nWoodard attended [[Myers Park High School]] in [[Charlotte, North Carolina]], where he played for the school's [[baseball]] teams where he pitched and played shortstop.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://goheels.com/news/2003/9/3/205479314.aspx |title=Meet Carolina's Freshmen Pitchers |date=September 3, 2003 |publisher=University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill Athletics |work=www.goheels.com |accessdate=July 1, 2019}}</ref> As a senior, the Team One South Showcase named Woodard a top 10 prospect. He also played on the Area Code National Team in the Japan Goodwill Series.\n\nThe all-time winningest pitcher in program history at UNC, Woodard posted a career record of 34\u20135 over four seasons as a Tar Heel. He was a three-time All-ACC performer and the 2006-07 recipient of the Patterson Medal, North Carolina's highest athletic honor. From 2004 to 2007, the Tar Heels won 195 games and advanced to back-to-back College World Series Finals in 2006 and 2007. In addition to the aforementioned career record of 34\u20135, Woodard finished his college career with a perfect 22\u20130 record at UNC's Boshamer Stadium. He also left Carolina ranking among the top 10 in Atlantic Coast Conference history in victories and innings pitched.\n\n==Head coaching record==\n\n{{CBB Yearly Record Start\n|type=coach\n|conference=\n|postseason=\n|poll=no\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subhead\n|name=[[Charlotte 49ers baseball|Charlotte 49ers]]\n|conference=[[Conference USA]]\n|startyear=2020\n|endyear=\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | season       = 2020\n | name         = Charlotte\n | overall      = 9\u20138\n | conference   = 0\u20130\n | confstanding = \n | postseason   = Season canceled due to [[COVID-19]]\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Charlotte\n | overall    = 9\u20138\n | confrecord = 0\u20130\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record End\n | overall = 9\u20138\n}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of current NCAA Division I baseball coaches]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{baseballstats|mlb=|espn=|br=|fangraphs=|brm=woodar001rob}}\n*[https://charlotte49ers.com/coaches.aspx?rc=846&path=baseball Charlotte 49ers profile]\n\n<!--{{Charlotte 49ers baseball coach navbox}}-->\n{{Conference USA baseball coach navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Woodard, Robert}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:North Carolina Tar Heels baseball players]]\n[[Category:Eugene Emeralds players]]\n[[Category:Portland Beavers players]]\n[[Category:Fort Wayne Wizards players]]\n[[Category:Lake Elsinore Storm players]]\n[[Category:North Carolina Tar Heels baseball coaches]]\n[[Category:UNC Wilmington Seahawks baseball coaches]]\n[[Category:Virginia Tech Hokies baseball coaches]]\n[[Category:Charlotte 49ers baseball coaches]]\n[[Category:People from Winston-Salem, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Baseball coaches from North Carolina]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox college coach\n| name               = Robert Woodard\n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| current_title      = [[Head coach]]\n| current_team       = [[Charlotte 49ers baseball|Charlotte]]\n| current_conference = [[Conference USA|C-USA]]\n| current_record     = 9\u20138\n| contract           = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1985|1|10}}\n| birth_place        = [[Winston-Salem, North Carolina]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| player_years1      = 2004\u20132007\n| player_team1       = [[North Carolina Tar Heels baseball|North Carolina]]\n| player_years2      = 2007\n| player_team2       = [[Eugene Emeralds]]\n| player_years3      = 2007\u20132008\n| player_team3       = [[Portland Beavers]]\n| player_years4      = 2008\n| player_team4       = [[Fort Wayne Wizards]]\n| player_years5      = 2008\u20132009\n| player_team5       = [[Lake Elsinore Storm]]\n| player_positions   = [[Pitcher]]\n| coach_years1       = 2010\u20132012\n| coach_team1        = North Carolina (asst)\n| coach_years2       = 2013\n| coach_team2        = [[UNC Wilmington Seahawks baseball|UNC Wilmington]] (asst)\n| coach_years3       = 2014\u20132016\n| coach_team3        = [[Virginia Tech Hokies baseball|Virginia Tech]] (asst)\n| coach_years4       = 2017\u20132019\n| coach_team4        = North Carolina (asst)\n| coach_years5       = 2020\u2013present\n| coach_team5        = [[Charlotte 49ers baseball|Charlotte]]\n| overall_record     = 9\u20138\n| tournament_record  = C-USA: 0\u20130<br>NCAA: 0\u20130\n| championships      = \n| awards             = \n| coaching_records   = \n| CBASEHOF_year      = \n}}\n\n'''Robert Suiter Woodard''' (born January 10, 1985) is an American baseball coach and former pitcher. He is the head baseball coach at the [[University of North Carolina at Charlotte]]. Woodard played [[college baseball]] at the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]] from 2004 to 2007 for coach [[Mike Fox (baseball)|Mike Fox]] and in [[Minor League Baseball]] (MiLB) for three seasons from 2007 to 2009.\n\nWoodard was born in [[Winston-Salem, North Carolina]]. He attended [[Myers Park High School]] in [[Charlotte, North Carolina]]. After graduation from high school, he decided to attend University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill to play baseball. After his junior season, he was selected by the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] in the [[2006 Major League Baseball draft]]'s 46th round. He returned to North Carolina for his senior season where he was drafted in the twentieth round of the [[2007 Major League Baseball draft]] by the [[San Diego Padres]].\n\nIn 2019, Woodard was named the head coach of the [[Charlotte 49ers baseball]] program.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/college/article232111957.html |title=Charlotte native and former UNC standout named 49ers baseball coach |author=David Scott |date=June 29, 2019 |publisher=Charlotte Observer |work=www.charlotteobserver.com |accessdate=July 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Amateur career==\nWoodard attended [[Myers Park High School]] in [[Charlotte, North Carolina]], where he played for the school's [[baseball]] teams where he pitched and played shortstop.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://goheels.com/news/2003/9/3/205479314.aspx |title=Meet Carolina's Freshmen Pitchers |date=September 3, 2003 |publisher=University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill Athletics |work=www.goheels.com |accessdate=July 1, 2019}}</ref> As a senior, the Team One South Showcase named Woodard a top 10 prospect. He also played on the Area Code National Team in the Japan Goodwill Series.\n\nThe all-time winningest pitcher in program history at UNC, Woodard posted a career record of 34-5 over four seasons as a Tar Heel. He was a three-time All-ACC performer and the 2006-07 recipient of the Patterson Medal, North Carolina\u2019s highest athletic honor. From 2004 to 2007, the Tar Heels won 195 games and advanced to back-to-back College World Series Finals in 2006 and 2007. In addition to the aforementioned career record of 34-5, Woodard finished his college career with a perfect 22-0 record at UNC's Boshamer Stadium. He also left Carolina ranking among the top 10 in Atlantic Coast Conference history in victories and innings pitched.\n\n==Head coaching record==\n\n{{CBB Yearly Record Start\n|type=coach\n|conference=\n|postseason=\n|poll=no\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subhead\n|name=[[Charlotte 49ers baseball|Charlotte 49ers]]\n|conference=[[Conference USA]]\n|startyear=2020\n|endyear=\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | season       = 2020\n | name         = Charlotte\n | overall      = 9\u20138\n | conference   = 0\u20130\n | confstanding = \n | postseason   = Season canceled due to [[COVID-19]]\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Charlotte\n | overall    = 9\u20138\n | confrecord = 0\u20130\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record End\n | overall = 9\u20138\n}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of current NCAA Division I baseball coaches]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{baseballstats|mlb=|espn=|br=|fangraphs=|brm=woodar001rob}}\n*[https://charlotte49ers.com/coaches.aspx?rc=846&path=baseball Charlotte 49ers profile]\n\n<!--{{Charlotte 49ers baseball coach navbox}}-->\n{{Conference USA baseball coach navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Woodard, Robert}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:North Carolina Tar Heels baseball players]]\n[[Category:Eugene Emeralds players]]\n[[Category:Portland Beavers players]]\n[[Category:Fort Wayne Wizards players]]\n[[Category:Lake Elsinore Storm players]]\n[[Category:North Carolina Tar Heels baseball coaches]]\n[[Category:UNC Wilmington Seahawks baseball coaches]]\n[[Category:Virginia Tech Hokies baseball coaches]]\n[[Category:Charlotte 49ers baseball coaches]]\n[[Category:People from Winston-Salem, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Baseball coaches from North Carolina]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAmateur career:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 34-5 \u2192 34\u20135 (2), \u2019s \u2192 's, 34-5 \u2192 34\u20135", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Woodard_(baseball)"}
{"title_page": "River Beane", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox river\n| name               = Beane\n| name_native        = \n| name_native_lang   = \n| name_other         = \n| name_etymology     = \n<!---------------------- IMAGE & MAP -->\n| image              = RiverBeaneHertford.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| image_caption      = Weir on the River Beane, Hartham Common\n| map                = \n| map_size           = \n| map_caption        = \n| pushpin_map        = \n| pushpin_map_size   = \n| pushpin_map_caption= \n<!---------------------- LOCATION -->\n| subdivision_type1  = Country\n| subdivision_name1  = [[United Kingdom]]\n| subdivision_type2  = \n| subdivision_name2  = \n| subdivision_type3  = \n| subdivision_name3  = \n| subdivision_type4  = \n| subdivision_name4  = \n| subdivision_type5  = \n| subdivision_name5  = \n<!---------------------- PHYSICAL CHARACTERISTICS -->\n| length             = {{convert|17.8|km|mi|abbr=on}} \n| width_min          = \n| width_avg          = \n| width_max          = \n| depth_min          = \n| depth_avg          = \n| depth_max          = \n| discharge1_location= \n| discharge1_min     = \n| discharge1_avg     = \n| discharge1_max     = \n<!---------------------- BASIN FEATURES -->\n| source1            = \n| source1_location   = Nr. [[Sandon, Hertfordshire|Sandon]], [[Hertfordshire]]\n| source1_coordinates= \n| source1_elevation  = {{convert|90|m|abbr=on}}\n| mouth              = \n| mouth_location     = [[Hertford]], [[Hertfordshire]]<br/>into [[River Lea]]\n| mouth_coordinates  = \n| mouth_elevation    = \n| progression        = \n| river_system       = \n| basin_size         = \n| tributaries_left   = \n| tributaries_right  = \n| custom_label       = \n| custom_data        = \n| extra              = \n}}\n\nThe '''River Beane''' is a short river in the county of Hertfordshire, England.  A tributary of the [[River Lea]], it rises to the south-west of [[Sandon, Hertfordshire|Sandon]] in the hills northeast of [[Stevenage]] and joins the Lea at [[Hartham Common]] in [[Hertford]].\n\n==Watermills==\nIn medieval times there were a number of [[watermill]]s along the course of the Beane. A few of the buildings and [[mill race]]s survive.\n* Sele Mill, Hertford, is perhaps the site with the most historical interest. It was mentioned in the [[Domesday Book]].<ref>[http://list.historicengland.org.uk/resultsingle_print.aspx?uid=1268844&showMap=1&showText=1 SELE HOUSE including front railings (1268844)]. [[Historic England]]</ref> Its main claim to fame is that in the 15th century the facility was converted for use as a [[paper mill]] and was, as far as is known, the earliest paper mill in England. It is not clear when paper production began there, although 1488 has been suggested,<ref name=\"OP\">{{cite web | url=http://openplaques.org/plaques/30561 | title=Sele Mill | publisher=Open Plaques | accessdate=23 June 2015}}</ref> but it was certainly underway in the 1490s. Paper from Sele Mill, supplied by [[John Tate (papermaker)|John Tate]], was used in publications from that decade, and the mill was visited by [[Henry VII of England|Henry VII]] in 1498 and 1499.  Despite this sign of royal favour, paper production did not continue there for long, and appears to have ceased by the time the paper maker [[John Tate (paper maker)|John Tate]] made his will in 1507.<ref>Richard L. Hills, \u2018Tate, John (c.1448\u20131507/8)\u2019, [[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]], Oxford University Press, 2004; online edn, Jan 2008 [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/58376, accessed 24 June 2015]. Subscription or UK public library membership required.</ref>\n* Walkern Mill, which was rebuilt in the 19th century, is a [[grade II listed]] building.<ref name=\"BLB\"></ref>\n\n==Abstraction==\nThe Beane valley remains mainly rural in character.  However, Hertfordshire's population increased substantially in the second half of the twentieth century, and the consequent demand for water has affected rivers such as the Beane and the [[River Mimram|Mimram]].  In the case of the Beane, a licence was given to abstract water near [[Aston, Hertfordshire|Aston]] for Stevenage's water supply. The river has since been adversely affected by over-exploitation of the chalk [[aquifer]] in its upper reaches. \n\nThe photo shows a dry section south of [[Walkern]] where from the 1990s until about 2014 there was only seasonal flow.  An indication of the scale of the decline in flow is that the section at Walkern was once big enough to power a watermill and to support [[watercress]] beds.<ref name=\"BLB\">[http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/en-159686-walkern-mill-and-number-161-millers-cott Walkern Mill]</ref>\n[[File:River Beane near Aston - geograph.org.uk - 172067.jpg|left|thumb|Dry bed of the Beane near [[Aston, Hertfordshire]] in 2006]]\nThe lower Beane is more robust and there has continued to be regular flow through [[Watton-at-Stone]], [[Stapleford, Hertfordshire|Stapleford]] and [[Waterford, Hertfordshire|Waterford]] until the confluence with the River Lea. However, overall the river has performed badly in assessments by the [[Environment Agency]] of flow level.\n\n==Restoration==\nThe state of the upper Beane resulted in calls for the river's restoration.<ref name=\"mercury\">{{cite web | url=http://www.hertfordshiremercury.co.uk/Campaigners-walk-dry-River-Beane/story-21998387-detail/story.html | title=Campaigners in walk along dry River Beane | work=[[Hertfordshire Mercury]] | date=2012 | accessdate=10 June 2016}}</ref>\nThe management plan for the river includes the objective that there is adequate flow along the length of the river to support a \u2018good status\u2019 [[chalk stream]] ecology (as defined by the [[European Union]]'s [[Water Framework Directive]]).\n<ref name=\"rlc\">[http://www.riverleacatchment.org.uk/index.php/river-beane-cmp/river-beane-themes-and-objectives River Beane: Catchment management plan] www.riverleacatchment.org.uk</ref>\n\nOne possible approach to the restoration of the upper Beane which was discussed was to use recycled water from [[sewage treatment]] works. Sewage from the Stevenage area bypassed the river, being pumped down the Beane valley to Rye Meads near Hertford for treatment and eventual discharge into the [[River Stort]]. However, the water could theoretically have been discharged into the Beane if treated further upstream.<ref>[http://www.eera.gov.uk/GetAsset.aspx?id=fAAzADAAOQB8AHwARgBhAGwAcwBlAHwAfAAwAHwA0 Waste Water Report], [[Halcrow Group]]</ref>\nIn the event another option was chosen. [[Affinity Water]] was told to take less water from its pumping station near Aston, even though obtaining water from a less environmentally damaging source was difficult as the River Lea's catchment area as a whole is under pressure.\n\nThere have been initiatives to improve the condition of lower stretches of the river, for example where it passes through the [[Woodhall Park|Woodhall Park estate]] near Watton. Here the river has been modified by an 18th-century landscaping project which had the adverse consequence of impeding [[Fish migration|fish passage]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.woodhallestate.co.uk/2018-06-the-broadwater-and-river-beane-renovation-project |title=Broadwater and River Beane renovation |date=2018 |website=Woodhall Estate |access-date=2019-03-03}}</ref>\n\n==Access==\n[[Herts and Middlesex Wildlife Trust]] (HMWT) has launched a circular trail at\n[[Waterford, Hertfordshire|Waterford]], which includes some scenic sections of the River\nBeane.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{commons category|River Beane}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.wwf.org.uk/wwf_articles.cfm?unewsid=3875 Press release for WWF report \"Riverside Tales\"], 2010-04-28, [[WWF-UK]]\n* [http://www.theyblogforyou.com/1413/2010-04-29/launch-of-the-wwf-report-on-the-rivers-beane-and-mimram ''Launch of the WWF report on the Rivers Beane and Mimram''], [[Oliver Heald]] MP comments on WWF report.\n* [http://www.riverleacatchment.org.uk/index.php/river-beane-home ''River Beane Catchment'']\n\n{{River Lee England}}\n{{Rivers and watercourses of Hertfordshire}}\n\n{{coord|51|47|N|0|05|W|display=title|region:GB_type:river_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of Hertfordshire|Beane]]\n[[Category:Tributaries of the River Lea|Beane]]\n[[Category:Lea catchment|1Beane]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox river\n| name               = Beane\n| name_native        = \n| name_native_lang   = \n| name_other         = \n| name_etymology     = \n<!---------------------- IMAGE & MAP -->\n| image              = RiverBeaneHertford.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| image_caption      = Weir on the River Beane, Hartham Common\n| map                = \n| map_size           = \n| map_caption        = \n| pushpin_map        = \n| pushpin_map_size   = \n| pushpin_map_caption= \n<!---------------------- LOCATION -->\n| subdivision_type1  = Country\n| subdivision_name1  = [[United Kingdom]]\n| subdivision_type2  = \n| subdivision_name2  = \n| subdivision_type3  = \n| subdivision_name3  = \n| subdivision_type4  = \n| subdivision_name4  = \n| subdivision_type5  = \n| subdivision_name5  = \n<!---------------------- PHYSICAL CHARACTERISTICS -->\n| length             = {{convert|17.8|km|mi|abbr=on}} \n| width_min          = \n| width_avg          = \n| width_max          = \n| depth_min          = \n| depth_avg          = \n| depth_max          = \n| discharge1_location= \n| discharge1_min     = \n| discharge1_avg     = \n| discharge1_max     = \n<!---------------------- BASIN FEATURES -->\n| source1            = \n| source1_location   = Nr. [[Sandon, Hertfordshire|Sandon]], [[Hertfordshire]]\n| source1_coordinates= \n| source1_elevation  = {{convert|90|m|abbr=on}}\n| mouth              = \n| mouth_location     = [[Hertford]], [[Hertfordshire]]<br/>into [[River Lea]]\n| mouth_coordinates  = \n| mouth_elevation    = \n| progression        = \n| river_system       = \n| basin_size         = \n| tributaries_left   = \n| tributaries_right  = \n| custom_label       = \n| custom_data        = \n| extra              = \n}}\n\nThe '''River Beane''' is a short river in the county of Hertfordshire, England.  A tributary of the [[River Lea]], it rises to the south-west of [[Sandon, Hertfordshire|Sandon]] in the hills northeast of [[Stevenage]] and joins the Lea at [[Hartham Common]] in [[Hertford]].\n\n==Watermills==\nIn medieval times there were a number of [[watermill]]s along the course of the Beane. A few of the buildings and [[mill race]]s survive.\n* Sele Mill, Hertford, is perhaps the site with the most historical interest. It was mentioned in the [[Domesday Book]].<ref>[http://list.historicengland.org.uk/resultsingle_print.aspx?uid=1268844&showMap=1&showText=1 SELE HOUSE including front railings (1268844)]. [[Historic England]]</ref> Its main claim to fame is that in the 15th century the facility was converted for use as a [[paper mill]] and was, as far as is known, the earliest paper mill in England. It is not clear when paper production began there, although 1488 has been suggested,<ref name=\"OP\">{{cite web | url=http://openplaques.org/plaques/30561 | title=Sele Mill | publisher=Open Plaques | accessdate=23 June 2015}}</ref> but it was certainly underway in the 1490s. Paper from Sele Mill, supplied by [[John Tate (papermaker)|John Tate]], was used in publications from that decade, and the mill was visited by [[Henry VII of England|Henry VII]] in 1498 and 1499.  Despite this sign of royal favour, paper production did not continue there for long, and appears to have ceased by the time the paper maker [[John Tate (paper maker)|John Tate]] made his will in 1507.<ref>Richard L. Hills, \u2018Tate, John (c.1448\u20131507/8)\u2019, [[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]], Oxford University Press, 2004; online edn, Jan 2008 [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/58376, accessed 24 June 2015]. Subscription or UK public library membership required.</ref>\n* Walkern Mill, which was rebuilt in the 19th century, is a [[grade II listed]] building.<ref name=\"BLB\"></ref>\n\n==Abstraction==\nThe Beane valley remains mainly rural in character.  However, Hertfordshire's population increased substantially in the second half of the twentieth century, and the consequent demand for water has affected rivers such as the Beane and the [[River Mimram|Mimram]].  In the case of the Beane, a licence was given to abstract water near [[Aston, Hertfordshire|Aston]] for Stevenage's water supply. The river has since been adversely affected by over-exploitation of the chalk [[aquifer]] in its upper reaches. \n\nThe photo shows a dry section south of [[Walkern]] where from the 1990s until about 2014 there was only seasonal flow.  An indication of the scale of the decline in flow is that the section at Walkern was once big enough to power a watermill and to support [[watercress]] beds.<ref name=\"BLB\">[http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/en-159686-walkern-mill-and-number-161-millers-cott Walkern Mill]</ref>\n[[File:River Beane near Aston - geograph.org.uk - 172067.jpg|left|thumb|Dry bed of the Beane near [[Aston, Hertfordshire]] in 2006]]\nThe lower Beane is more robust and there has continued to be regular flow through [[Watton-at-Stone]], [[Stapleford, Hertfordshire|Stapleford]] and [[Waterford, Hertfordshire|Waterford]] until the confluence with the River Lea. However, overall the river has performed badly in assessments by the [[Environment Agency]] of flow level.\n\n==Restoration==\nThe state of the upper Beane resulted in calls for the river\u00b4s restoration.<ref name=\"mercury\">{{cite web | url=http://www.hertfordshiremercury.co.uk/Campaigners-walk-dry-River-Beane/story-21998387-detail/story.html | title=Campaigners in walk along dry River Beane | work=[[Hertfordshire Mercury]] | date=2012 | accessdate=10 June 2016}}</ref>\nThe management plan for the river includes the objective that there is adequate flow along the length of the river to support a \u2018good status\u2019 [[chalk stream]] ecology (as defined by the [[European Union]]'s [[Water Framework Directive]]).\n<ref name=\"rlc\">[http://www.riverleacatchment.org.uk/index.php/river-beane-cmp/river-beane-themes-and-objectives River Beane: Catchment management plan] www.riverleacatchment.org.uk</ref>\n\nOne possible approach to the restoration of the upper Beane which was discussed was to use recycled water from [[sewage treatment]] works. Sewage from the Stevenage area bypassed the river, being pumped down the Beane valley to Rye Meads near Hertford for treatment and eventual discharge into the [[River Stort]]. However, the water could theoretically have been discharged into the Beane if treated further upstream.<ref>[http://www.eera.gov.uk/GetAsset.aspx?id=fAAzADAAOQB8AHwARgBhAGwAcwBlAHwAfAAwAHwA0 Waste Water Report], [[Halcrow Group]]</ref>\nIn the event another option was chosen. [[Affinity Water]] was told to take less water from its pumping station near Aston, even though obtaining water from a less environmentally damaging source was difficult as the River Lea's catchment area as a whole is under pressure.\n\nThere have been initiatives to improve the condition of lower stretches of the river, for example where it passes through the [[Woodhall Park|Woodhall Park estate]] near Watton. Here the river has been modified by an 18th century landscaping project which had the adverse consequence of impeding [[Fish migration|fish passage]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.woodhallestate.co.uk/2018-06-the-broadwater-and-river-beane-renovation-project |title=Broadwater and River Beane renovation |date=2018 |website=Woodhall Estate |access-date=2019-03-03}}</ref>\n\n==Access==\n[[Herts and Middlesex Wildlife Trust]] (HMWT) has launched a circular trail at\n[[Waterford, Hertfordshire|Waterford]], which includes some scenic sections of the River\nBeane.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{commons category|River Beane}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.wwf.org.uk/wwf_articles.cfm?unewsid=3875 Press release for WWF report \"Riverside Tales\"], 2010-04-28, [[WWF-UK]]\n* [http://www.theyblogforyou.com/1413/2010-04-29/launch-of-the-wwf-report-on-the-rivers-beane-and-mimram ''Launch of the WWF report on the Rivers Beane and Mimram''], [[Oliver Heald]] MP comments on WWF report.\n* [http://www.riverleacatchment.org.uk/index.php/river-beane-home ''River Beane Catchment'']\n\n{{River Lee England}}\n{{Rivers and watercourses of Hertfordshire}}\n\n{{coord|51|47|N|0|05|W|display=title|region:GB_type:river_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of Hertfordshire|Beane]]\n[[Category:Tributaries of the River Lea|Beane]]\n[[Category:Lea catchment|1Beane]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRestoration:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: an 18th century \u2192 an 18th-century, \u00b4s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/River_Beane"}
{"title_page": "Ad\u00e8le Haenel", "text_new": "{{short description|French actress}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image              = Ad\u00e8le Haenel Cannes 2017.jpg\n| caption            = Haenel at the [[2017 Cannes Film Festival]]\n| name               = Ad\u00e8le Haenel\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=no|1989|2|11}}\n| birth_place        = [[Paris]], France\n| nationality        = French\n| occupation         = Actress\n| yearsactive        = 2002\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Ad\u00e8le Haenel''' ({{IPA-fr|ad\u025bl en\u025bl|lang}}; born 1 January 1989<ref name=MarieClaire>{{cite web |last=Bourdon |first=Megan |date=5 November 2019 |title=Ad\u00e8le Haenel, actrice sans fards et r\u00e9sistante |url=https://www.marieclaire.fr/adele-haenel,1324009.asp |newspaper=[[Marie Claire]] |language=French |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://madame.lefigaro.fr/personnalite/adele-haenel|title=Ad\u00e8le Haenel|work=Madame Figaro|accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Descamps|first=Quentin|date=13 March 2015|url=https://next.liberation.fr/cinema/2015/03/13/adele-haenel-la-belle-degenree_1220155|title=Ad\u00e8le Haenel, la belle d\u00e9genr\u00e9e|work=Lib\u00e9ration|accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rtl.fr/culture/cine-series/cesar-2015-adele-haenel-remporte-le-cesar-de-la-meilleure-actrice-7776692677|title=C\u00e9sar 2015 : Ad\u00e8le Haenel remporte le C\u00e9sar de la meilleure actrice|publisher=RTL|date=21 February 2015|accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref>) is a French actress. She is the recipient of several accolades, including two [[C\u00e9sar Award]]s from seven nominations and one [[Lumi\u00e8res Award]] from two nominations.\n\nHaenel began her career as a child actress, making her film debut with ''[[Les Diables]]'' (2002) at the age of 12, and quickly rose to prominence in the French entertainment industry as a teenager. She received her first C\u00e9sar Award nomination for her performance in ''[[Water Lilies (film)|Water Lilies]]'' (2007), which also marked the beginning of her long professional and personal relationship with director [[C\u00e9line Sciamma]]. In 2014, Haenel received her first C\u00e9sar Award for her supporting role in ''[[Suzanne (2013 film)|Suzanne]]'', and in 2015 won the [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Actress]] for ''[[Love at First Fight (film)|Love at First Fight]]''. She continued to garner recognition for her performances in ''[[BPM (Beats per Minute)]]'' (2017), ''[[The Trouble with You]]'' (2018) and ''[[Portrait of a Lady on Fire]]'' (2019).\n\n== Early life ==\nHaenel was born on 1 January 1989 in [[Paris]],<ref name=MarieClaire/> and grew up in [[Montreuil, Seine-Saint-Denis]] in what she described as \"a very left-wing, artistic neighborhood\".<ref name=FilmComment>{{cite web |date=24 May 2019 |last1=Rapold |first1=Nicolas |title=Interview: Ad\u00e8le Haenel |url=https://www.filmcomment.com/blog/cannes-interview-adele-haenel/ |newspaper=[[Film Comment]] |accessdate=7 January 2020}}</ref> Her mother is a teacher and her father is a translator.<ref name=MarieClaire/> She has Austrian heritage through her father and speaks some German.<ref name=FilmComment/><ref name=Grazia>{{cite web |last=Puyremond |first=Zo\u00e9 |date=7 February 2020 |title=8 choses que vous ne savez (peut-\u00eatre) pas sur Ad\u00e8le Haenel |url=https://www.grazia.fr/people/8-choses-que-vous-ne-savez-peut-etre-pas-sur-adele-haenel-949965 |newspaper=[[Grazia]] |language=French |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> Haenel started acting at the age of 5 and was involved in local theatre.<ref name=LeMondeGallot2014>{{cite web |last=Gallot |first=Cl\u00e9mentine |date=11 July 2014 |title=La belle vie d'Ad\u00e8le Haenel |url=https://www.lemonde.fr/m-actu/article/2014/07/11/la-belle-vie-d-adele_4454943_4497186.html |newspaper=[[Le Monde]] |language=French |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> As a child, Haenel would mimic cartoon characters, particularly the characters of [[Tex Avery]].<ref name=FranceInfo>{{cite web |last=Vandel |first=Philippe |date=14 November 2016 |title=Tout et son contraire. Ad\u00e8le Haenel: \"Je pr\u00e9f\u00e8re mettre un justaucorps vert plut\u00f4t que d'aller d\u00eener au Fouquet's\" |url=https://www.francetvinfo.fr/replay-radio/tout-et-son-contraire/tout-et-son-contraire-adele-haenel-je-prefere-mettre-un-juste-au-corps-vert-plutot-que-d-aller-diner-au-fouquet-s_1909935.html |newspaper=[[France Info (radio network)|France Info]] |language=French |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nHaenel studied economics and social sciences at the [[Lyc\u00e9e Montaigne (Paris)|Lyc\u00e9e Montaigne]].<ref name=Politiquelles>{{cite web |date=15 November 2019 |title=#3 Portraits de Femmes : Ad\u00e8le Haenel |url=https://politiquelles.org/3-portraits-de-femmes-adele-haenel/ |newspaper=Politiqu'elles |language=French |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> She had planned to attend [[HEC Paris]] and took a preparatory course, but ultimately failed the entrance exam.<ref name=Grazia/> Haenel continued her studies in economics and sociology, eventually receiving a master's degree.<ref name=Elle2012>{{cite web |date=30 March 2012  |title=Ad\u00e8le Haenel, actrice sans fards et r\u00e9sistante |url=https://www.elle.fr/People/La-vie-des-people/Une-journee-avec/Une-journee-avec-Adele-Haenel-1976016 |newspaper=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle ]] |language=French |accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref> She also pursued studies in physics and marine biology.<ref>{{cite web |last=M\u00e9dioni |first=Gilles |date=16 March 2016 |title=Les Ogres. Ad\u00e8le Haenel: \"Ne valorisons pas trop la souffrance\"  |url=https://www.lexpress.fr/culture/cinema/les-ogres-adele-haenel-ne-valorisons-pas-trop-la-souffrance_1769741.html |newspaper=[[L'Express]] |language=French |accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nHaenel made her film debut in 2002 at the age of 12, playing an autistic girl in the {{Interlanguage link|Christophe Ruggia|fr}} film ''[[Les Diables]]''.<ref name=Guardian2019Chrisafis>{{cite web |last=Chrisafis |first=Angelique |date=5 November 2019 |title=French actor Ad\u00e8le Haenel claims director sexually harassed her |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/05/french-actor-adele-haenel-alleges-she-was-sexually-harassed-by-director |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> She had been chosen for the lead role after accompanying her brother to the audition.<ref name=LExpress2014>{{cite web |last=M\u00e9dioni |first=Gilles |date=16 July 2014 |title=Qui est Ad\u00e8le Haenel, C\u00e9sar 2015 de la meilleure actrice? |url=https://www.lexpress.fr/culture/cinema/adele-haenel-star-nouvelle-generation_1554363.html |newspaper=[[L'Express]] |language=French |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> After ''Les Diables'', Haenel took a five-year break from acting.<ref name=MarieClaire/> In 2007, she was persuaded by casting director Christel Baras (who had cast her in her film debut) to resume her film career, taking up the part of a [[synchronised swimming|synchronised swimmer]] in [[C\u00e9line Sciamma]]'s debut feature ''[[Water Lilies (film)|Water Lilies]]''.<ref name=LExpress2014/> [[Manohla Dargis]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' highlighted Haenel's performance in an otherwise mixed review of the film, recognizing her as having \"the makings of a real star\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Dargis |first=Manohla |date=4 April 2008 |title=Crossing Into the Deep End, Where Desire Is Fathomed |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/04/movies/04lili.html?ref=movies |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> For her role in the film, Haenel was nominated for the [[C\u00e9sar Award for Most Promising Actress]] in 2008.<ref name=Crash>{{cite web |last=Leturcq |first=Armelle |date=5 November 2019 |title=Adele Haenel on Film |url=https://www.crash.fr/adele-haenel-on-film-crash-magazine/ |newspaper=[[Crash Magazine]] |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> In 2012, she was nominated in the same category for ''[[House of Tolerance]]'' (2011),<ref name=Cesar2012>{{cite web |last=Tartaglione |first=Nancy |date=25 January 2012 |title='The Artist' Nabs 10 C\u00e9sar Nominations, But Maiwenn's 'Poliss' Leads With 13 Nods |url=https://deadline.com/2012/01/artist-nabs-10-cesar-nominations-but-maiwenns-poliss-leads-with-13-nods-221370/ |newspaper=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> a period film directed by [[Bertrand Bonello]], in which she played a prostitute at an upscale Parisian brothel at the turn of the twentieth century.<ref name=ArtForum>{{cite web |last=Anderson |first=Melissa |date=1 June 2018 |title=French, Open: Melissa Anderson on Ad\u00e8le Haenel |url=https://www.artforum.com/print/201806/melissa-anderson-on-adele-haenel-75512 |newspaper=[[Artforum]] |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> She also received the [[Lumi\u00e8res Award for Most Promising Actress]] along with her co-stars [[C\u00e9line Sallette]] and Alice Barnole.<ref name=Lumiere2012>{{cite web |last=Leffler |first=Rebecca |date=13 January 2012 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/the-artist-lumiere-awards-281420 |title='The Artist' Named Best Film at France's Lumiere Awards |accessdate=1 March 2020 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ad\u00e8le Haenel C\u00e9sars 2014.jpg|thumb|Haenel in 2014, receiving her first C\u00e9sar Award for ''[[Suzanne (2013 film)|Suzanne]]'']]\n\nHaenel played one of the two sisters in [[Katell Quill\u00e9v\u00e9r\u00e9]]'s ''[[Suzanne (2013 film)|Suzanne]]'' (2013),<ref name=ArtForum/> for which she received the [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Supporting Actress]].<ref name=Cesar2014>{{cite web |last=Richford |first=Rhonda |date=28 February 2014 |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cesar-awards-winners-list-684357 |title=France's Cesar Awards: ''Me, Myself and Mum'' Wins Best Film |accessdate=3 May 2014 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref> In 2014, Haenel starred in the [[Thomas Cailley]] romantic comedy ''[[Love at First Fight (film)|Love at First Fight]]'' as Madeleine, a graduate-school dropout and [[Survivalism|survivalist]].<ref name=ArtForum/> She won the [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Actress]] for her performance.<ref name=Cesar2015>{{cite web|last=Richford |first=Rhonda |date=20 February 2015 |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/2015-cesar-awards-winners-list-775695|title=Cesar Awards: 'Timbktu' Sweeps, Kristen Stewart Makes History|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> In the same year, Haenel co-starred with [[Catherine Deneuve]] in [[Andr\u00e9 T\u00e9chin\u00e9]]'s crime drama ''[[In the Name of My Daughter]]'', playing the daughter of a casino owner. Writing for ''[[The Village Voice]]'', Melissa Anderson compared her performance to that of [[Isabelle Adjani]]'s in the 1970s and '80s, and declared her a worthy successor to Deneuve in French cinema.<ref>{{cite web |last=Anderson |first=Melissa |date=20 May 2015 |url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2015/05/20/in-love-at-first-fight-adele-haenel-burns-through-our-screens/ |title=In Love at First Fight, Adele Haenel Burns Through Our Screens |accessdate=1 March 2020 |work=[[The Village Voice]]}}</ref> For her roles in both films, Hanael received a [[Lumi\u00e8res Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] nomination at the [[20th Lumi\u00e8res Awards]].<ref name=Lumiere2015>{{cite web |last=Richford |first=Rhonda |date=12 January 2015 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/frances-lumiere-awards-nominations-unveiled-762567 |title=France's Lumiere Awards Nominations Unveiled |accessdate=1 March 2020 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 Haenel made her German language debut in the film ''[[The Bloom of Yesterday]]'' playing the French descendant of German Holocaust survivors.\n\nIn the 2017 [[Robin Campillo]] film ''[[BPM (Beats per Minute)]]'', Haenel portrayed Sophie, a headstrong [[HIV/AIDS]] activist of the Paris chapter of [[ACT UP]].<ref name=ArtForum/> She received a nomination for the C\u00e9sar Award for Best Supporting Actress for her performance.<ref name=Cesar2018>{{cite web|last=Richford |first=Rhonda |date=2 March 2018 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/cesar-awards-2018-winners-list-1089548/item/best-film-1079713|title=Cesar Awards: '120 BPM' Takes Six Awards Including Best Film|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nHaenel starred in the 2018 [[Pierre Salvadori]] crime comedy ''[[The Trouble with You]]'', playing a widowed detective based on the [[French Riviera]]. David Rooney of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' noted her performance as evoking the \"classic screwball heroine\", a departure from her usually more serious roles, and complimented her on the \"grace and buoyancy\" she brought to the character.<ref>{{cite web |date=15 May 2018 |last=Rooney |first=David |title='The Trouble With You' ('En Liberte!'): Film Review Cannes 2018 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/trouble-with-you-en-liberte-cannes-2018-1112275 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> She was again nominated for the [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Actress]].<ref name=Cesar2019>{{cite web |date=January 23, 2019 |last=Keslassy |first=Elsa |title=\u2018Sink or Swim,\u2019 \u2018Custody\u2019 Lead Race for France\u2019s Cesar Awards |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/cesar-nominations-sink-or-swim-custody-lead-race-1203115394/ |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Haenel appeared in three films which played at the [[2019 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes Film Festival]]: [[Mr. Oizo|Quentin Dupieux]]'s ''[[Deerskin (film)|Deerskin]]'', Aude L\u00e9a Rapin's ''Heroes Don't Die'', and C\u00e9line Sciamma's ''[[Portrait of a Lady on Fire]]''.<ref>{{cite web |date=May 20, 2019  |last=Lodge |first=Guy |title=Cannes Film Review: \u2018Heroes Don\u2019t Die\u2019 |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/reviews/heroes-dont-die-review-1203221561/ |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> In ''Portrait of a Lady on Fire'', Haenel portrayed H\u00e9lo\u00efse, a young aristocrat in 18th-century [[Brittany]] who is to be married off to a nobleman from Milan. ''[[The New Yorker]]'''s [[Richard Brody]] took note of her chemistry with co-star [[No\u00e9mie Merlant]] and complimented the actresses for being \"relentlessly graceful, endowed with physical aplomb, contemplative insight, and strong emotion\".<ref>{{cite web |date=December 10, 2019 |last=Brody |first=Richard |title=Speaking for Women\u2019s Art in \u201cPortrait of a Lady on Fire\u201d |url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/the-front-row/speaking-for-womens-art-in-portrait-of-a-lady-on-fire-review |website=[[The New Yorker]] |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> [[A. O. Scott]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' considered Haenel's performance worthy of an Oscar nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]],<ref>{{cite web |date=3 January 2020 |last1=Dargis |first1=Manohla |last2=Scott |first2=A.O. |title=And the 2020 Oscar Nominees Should Be \u2026 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/01/03/movies/critics-oscar-nominees.html?searchResultPosition=14 |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> and [[Bilge Ebiri]] of ''[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]'' described the climax of the film (which features Haenel) as \"one of the finest pieces of acting and one of the most moving images I\u2019ve seen in eons.\"<ref>{{cite web |date=12 February 2020 |last1=Ebiri |first1=Bilge |title=Portrait of a Lady on Fire Is a Grand, Capital-R Romance |url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/02/portrait-of-a-lady-on-fire-movie-review.html |website=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]] |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> Haenel was nominated for the [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Actress]] for her performance, her seventh C\u00e9sar nomination.<ref name=Cesar2020Nom>{{cite web |date=January 29, 2020 |last1=Tartaglione |first1=Nancy |title=C\u00e9sar Awards Nominations: Roman Polanski\u2019s \u2018An Officer And A Spy\u2019 Leads With 12; Ladj Ly\u2019s \u2018Les Mis\u00e9rables\u2019 Scores 11 \u2013 Full List |url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/cesar-awards-nominations-2020-roman-polanski-les-miserables-portrait-of-a-lady-on-fire-full-list-1202845041/ |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2014, Haenel [[Coming out|came out]] as lesbian during her C\u00e9sar award acceptance speech and acknowledged her relationship with director [[C\u00e9line Sciamma]], whom she met on the set of ''Water Lilies''.<ref name=\"JRomney\">{{cite web |first=Jonathan|last=Romney|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2016/dec/04/adele-haenel-unknown-girl-inteview-dardenne|title=Adele Haenel, 'Recycling cliches is a sign that a film lacks courage' |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=4 December 2016 |access-date=8 December 2016}}</ref> The couple amicably split in 2018, shortly before they began work on ''Portrait of a Lady on Fire''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Erbland |first1=Kate |title=\u2018Portrait of a Lady on Fire\u2019 Filmmaker C\u00e9line Sciamma Is Trying to Break Your Heart |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/portrait-of-a-lady-on-fire-filmmaker-celine-sciamma-interview-1202193537/ |accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref> In 2018, she was in a relationship with musician and singer Julia Lano\u00eb from the band [[Sexy Sushi]]. \n\nHaenel identifies as a [[feminist]].<ref name=MarieClaire/> She is a prominent face of France's [[Me Too movement|#MeToo]] movement,<ref name=\"RT\">{{cite web |title=MeToo movement |url=https://www.rt.com/news/481980-cesar-awards-polanski-metoo/ |website=rt.com |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web |last=Schofield|first=Hugh|date=7 November 2019|title=Ad\u00e8le Haenel MeToo moment shocks French cinema |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-50322452 |website=[[BBC]] |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> and was the first prominent actress to speak publicly about abuse within the French film industry.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite web |last=Peltier|first=Elian|date=24 February 2020|title=Ad\u00e8le Haenel: France \u2018Missed the Boat\u2019 on #MeToo |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/24/movies/adele-haenel-france-metoo.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> In a November 2019 ''[[Mediapart]]'' interview, Haenel accused director Christophe Ruggia of [[sexual harassment|sexually harassing]] her from the time she was 12 to 15 after casting her in his film ''Les Diables''.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Chu |first1=Henry |last2=Keslassy|first2=Elsa |title=\u2018Portrait of a Lady on Fire\u2019 Star Adele Haenel Accuses Director of Years of Harassment |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/global/portrait-of-a-lady-on-fire-adele-haenel-accuses-christophe-ruggia-harassment-1203391576/ |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=4 November 2019|accessdate=4 November 2019}}</ref> Following the experience, she considered abandoning acting altogether.<ref name=Guardian2019Chrisafis/> Haenel's account was backed up by many people who had worked on the film and noted Ruggia's inappropriate behaviour towards her, along with letters he had written her at the time proclaiming his love for her.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Grater |first1=Tom |title=French Actress Ad\u00e8le Haenel Accuses Director Christophe Ruggia Of Sexually Harassing Her From Age 12; He Denies Allegations |url=https://deadline.com/2019/11/portrait-of-a-lady-on-fire-adele-haenel-accuses-french-director-christophe-ruggia-underage-sexual-harassment-1202776553/ |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=4 November 2019|accessdate=4 November 2019}}</ref> As a result Ruggia was expelled from the Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des r\u00e9alisateurs de films, the guild for French directors.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mintzer |first1=Jordan |title=Christophe Ruggia, French Filmmaker Accused of Sexual Harassment, Is Fired From Directors\u2019 Association |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/christophe-ruggia-accused-sexually-harassing-actress-adele-haenel-1252232 |magazine=[[Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Eldridge Industries]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=4 November 2019|accessdate=4 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"\u201ccnn\u201d\">{{cite web|first=Saskya|last=Vandoorne|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/11/07/europe/adele-haenel-sexual-abuse-claims-intl/index.html|title=French film star Adele Haenel accuses director of abuse|website=[[CNN]]|publisher=[[Turner Broadcasting Systems]]|location=Atlanta, Georgia|date=8 November 2019|accessdate=23 November 2019}}</ref><ref>O'Connor, Roisin (7 November 2019). [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/adele-haenel-sexual-harassment-christophe-ruggia-director-teenager-france-a9188881.html \"Adele Haenel: French film industry rocked by childhood sexual harassment allegations against director Christophe Ruggia.\"] ''[[The Independent]]''. Retrieved 1 March 2020.</ref> Though Haenel had explicitly chosen not to go to the police with her accusations, citing the justice system as \"usually condemning so few sexual offenders\" and \"only one rape out of a hundred\" and stating that \"the justice ignores us, we ignore the justice\",<ref name=Mediapart>{{cite web |last=Turchi |first=Marine |date=3 November 2019 |title=#MeToo dans le cin\u00e9ma: l\u2019actrice Ad\u00e8le Haenel brise un nouveau tabou |url=https://www.mediapart.fr/journal/france/031119/metoo-dans-le-cinema-l-actrice-adele-haenel-brise-un-nouveau-tabou?page_article=1, |newspaper=[[Mediapart]] |language=French |url-access=subscription |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> the publicity garnered by her interviews about the abuse led the Paris prosecutor's office to announce they were investigating Ruggia.<ref name=\u201ccnn\u201d/> Haenel later changed her mind about working with the police and officially filed a complaint against Ruggia in late November 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=KESLASSY |first1=ELSA |title=Adele Haenel Files Police Complaint Against French Director |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/adele-haenel-police-complaint-against-french-director-christophe-ruggia-1203416872/ |accessdate=7 January 2020}}</ref> In January 2020, the police officially charged Ruggia with sexual aggression against a minor by a person of authority and sexual harassment.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Grater |first1=Tom |title=French Director Christophe Ruggia Formally Charged By Paris Prosecutors In Adele Haenel Sexual Assault Case |url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/french-director-christophe-ruggia-formally-charged-paris-prosecutors-adele-haenel-1202832599/}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 February 2020, Haenel walked out of the [[45th C\u00e9sar Awards]] ceremony after [[Roman Polanski]], who was [[Roman Polanski sexual abuse case|convicted of raping 13-year old Samantha Geimer]], won the award for [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Director|Best Director]] for his film ''[[An Officer and a Spy (film)|An Officer and a Spy]]''. As Haenel left, she cried \u201cShame!\u201d, and after exiting the auditorium, she was filmed clapping sarcastically and shouting \"Bravo la p\u00e9dophilie!\" (\"Well done, pedophile!\").<ref name=\"MadameFigaro2020\">{{cite web |date=29 February 2020 |title=\"Bravo la p\u00e9dophilie\" : le coup de col\u00e8re d'Ad\u00e8le Haenel apr\u00e8s la victoire de Roman Polanski aux C\u00e9sar |url=https://madame.lefigaro.fr/societe/on-est-un-peu-tendues-celine-sciamma-et-adele-haenel-sexpriment-sur-la-polemique-roman-polanski-aux-cesar-280220-180093 |website=[[Madame Figaro]] |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n|-\n| 2002 || ''[[Les Diables]]'' || Chlo\u00e9 || \n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[Water Lilies (film)|Water Lilies]]'' || Floriane || \n|-\n| 2009 || ''D\u00e9cha\u00een\u00e9es'' || Lucie || TV movie\n|-\n| 2010 || ''Adieu Molitor'' || La copine de Paulin  || Short film\n|-\n| 2010 || ''Les Grandes For\u00eats'' || Lise || Short film\n|-\n| 2010 || ''Pauline'' || || Short film\n|-\n| 2011 || ''[[Iris in Bloom]]'' || Isabelle || \n|-\n| 2011 || ''[[House of Tolerance]]'' || L\u00e9a || \n|-\n| 2011 || ''[[Heat Wave (2011 film)|Heat Wave]]'' || Am\u00e9lie || \n|-\n| 2011 || ''Les Enfantants de la Nuit''  || Heriette || Short film\n|-\n| 2011 || ''Goldman'' || Jeanne || TV movie \n|-\n| 2012 || ''Folks'' ||  || Short film\n|-\n| 2012 || ''[[Alyah]]'' || Jeanne || \n|-\n| 2012 || ''[[Three Worlds (film)|Three Worlds]]'' || Marion Testard || \n|-\n| 2012 || ''La Mouette'' || Macha || TV movie\n|-\n| 2013 || ''[[Suzanne (2013 film)|Suzanne]]'' || Maria || \n|-\n| 2014 || ''[[Love at First Fight (film)|Love at First Fight]]'' || Madeleine ||\n|-\n| 2014 || ''[[In the Name of My Daughter]]'' || Agn\u00e8s Le Roux || \n|-\n| 2015 || ''[[The Forbidden Room (2015 film)|The Forbidden Room]]'' || The Mute Invalid ||\n|-\n| 2015 || ''[[Les Ogres]]'' ||  Mona ||\n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[The Unknown Girl]]'' || Jenny ||\n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[Nocturama (film)|Nocturama]]'' || Girl with a bike ||\n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[Orphan (2016 film)|Orphan]]'' || Ren\u00e9e ||\n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[Seances (film)|Seances]]'' ||  ||\n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[The Bloom of Yesterday]]'' || Zazie ||\n|-\n| 2017 || ''[[BPM (Beats per Minute)]]'' || Sophie ||\n|-\n| 2018 || ''[[The Trouble With You]]'' || Yvonne ||\n|-\n| 2018 || ''[[One Nation, One King]]'' || Fran\u00e7oise ||\n|-\n| 2019 || ''[[Portrait of a Lady on Fire]]'' || H\u00e9lo\u00efse||\n|-\n| 2019 || ''[[Deerskin (film)|Deerskin]]'' || Denise||\n|-\n| 2019 || ''[[Heroes Don't Die]]'' || Alice||\n|}\n\n==Theatre==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Production\n! Director\n! Venue\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[The Seagull]]''\n|Arthur Nauzyciel\n|[[Festival d'Avignon]]\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''Le Moche / Voir Clair / Perplexe''\n|Ma\u00efa Sandoz\n|Th\u00e9\u00e2tre La G\u00e9n\u00e9rale, Paris\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Old Times]]''\n|Beno\u00eet Giros\n|[[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre de l'Atelier]]\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[The Ritual Slaughter of Gorge Mastromas]]''\n|Ma\u00efa Sandoz\n|CDN d'Orl\u00e9ans\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''Za\u00ef Za\u00ef Za\u00ef Za\u00ef''\n|Paul Moulin\n|Ferme du Buisson\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{|class = \"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n! Ref\n|-\n| 2008\n| [[33rd C\u00e9sar Awards|C\u00e9sar Awards]]\n|[[C\u00e9sar Award for Most Promising Actress|Most Promising Actress]]\n| ''[[Water Lilies (film)|Water Lilies]]''\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref name=Crash/>\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2012\n| [[Berlin International Film Festival]]\n|[[Shooting Stars Award]]\n|{{n/a}}\n| {{won}}\n|\n|-\n| [[17th Lumi\u00e8res Awards|Lumi\u00e8res Awards]]\n|[[Lumi\u00e8res Award for Most Promising Actress|Most Promising Actress]]\n| rowspan=2|''[[House of Tolerance]]''\n| {{won}}\n| <ref name=Lumiere2012/>\n|-\n| [[37th C\u00e9sar Awards|C\u00e9sar Awards]]\n|[[C\u00e9sar Award for Most Promising Actress|Most Promising Actress]]\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref name=Cesar2012/>\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2014\n| [[39th C\u00e9sar Awards|C\u00e9sar Awards]]\n|[[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]]\n| ''[[Suzanne (2013 film)|Suzanne]]''\n| {{won}}\n| <ref name=Cesar2014/>\n|-\n| [[Prix Suzanne Bianchetti]]\n| {{n/a}}\n| {{n/a}}\n| {{won}}\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=6|2015\n| [[40th C\u00e9sar Awards|C\u00e9sar Awards]]\n| [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n| rowspan=3|''[[Love at First Fight (film)|Love at First Fight]]''\n| {{won}}\n| <ref name=Cesar2015/>\n|-\n| [[Cairo International Film Festival]]\n| Best Actress\n| {{won}}\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[20th Lumi\u00e8res Awards|Lumi\u00e8res Awards]]\n| [[Lumi\u00e8res Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref name=Lumiere2015/>\n|-\n|[[Lumi\u00e8res Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n| ''[[In the Name of My Daughter]]''\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref name=Lumiere2015/>\n|-\n| [[Prix Romy Schneider]]\n|{{n/a}}\n|{{n/a}}\n| {{won}}\n|\n|-\n| [[Globes de Cristal Awards]]\n| [[Globe de Cristal Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n| ''[[Love at First Fight (film)|Love at First Fight]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| [[Festival International du Film Francophone de Namur]]\n|Best Actress\n| ''[[Orphan (2016 film)|Orphan]]''\n| {{won}}\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| [[43rd C\u00e9sar Awards|C\u00e9sar Awards]]\n| [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]]\n| ''[[BPM (Beats per Minute)]]''\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref name=Cesar2018/>\n|-\n| rowspan=6| 2019\n| [[44th C\u00e9sar Awards|C\u00e9sar Awards]]\n| [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n| rowspan=2| ''[[The Trouble with You]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n| [[Globe de Cristal Awards]]\n| [[Globe de Cristal Award for Best Actress|Best Actress - Comedy]]\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n| [[32nd European Film Awards|European Film Awards]]\n| [[European Film Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n| rowspan=5| ''[[Portrait of a Lady on Fire]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[IndieWire Critics Poll]]\n| Best Actress\n| {{no|10th Place}}\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\" |<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/best-movies-2019-critics-survey-poll-performances-parasite-adam-driver-lupita-nyongo-1202197615/|title=2019 Critics Poll: The Best Films and Performances According to Over 300 Critics From Around the World|last=Kohn|first=Eric|date=16 December 2019|website=[[IndieWire]]|url-status=live|accessdate=12 February 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Supporting Actress\n| {{no|13th Place}}\n|-\n| [[Austin Film Critics Association]]\n| Best Supporting Actress\n| {{nom}}\n| align=\"center\" |<ref>{{cite web|url=https://austinfilmcritics.org/2019-awards-d2faafe15279|title=2019 Awards|last=Stoddard|first=Elizabeth|date=7 January 2020|website=[[Austin Film Critics Association]]|url-status=live|accessdate=12 February 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2020\n| [[45th C\u00e9sar Awards|C\u00e9sar Awards]]\n| [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref name=Cesar2020Nom/>\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Ad\u00e8le Haenel}}\n*{{IMDb name|1194748}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Ad\u00e8le Haenel\n|list =\n{{C\u00e9sar Award for Best Actress}}\n{{C\u00e9sar Award for Best Supporting Actress}}\n{{Lumi\u00e8res Award for Most Promising Actress}}\n{{Prix Suzanne Bianchetti}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haenel, Adele}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:French film actresses]]\n[[Category:French television actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century French actresses]]\n[[Category:French people of Austrian descent]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Paris]]\n[[Category:French stage actresses]]\n[[Category:French people of German descent]]\n[[Category:Most Promising Actress Lumi\u00e8res Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Supporting Actress C\u00e9sar Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Actress C\u00e9sar Award winners]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from France]]\n[[Category:Lesbian actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses of German descent]]\n[[Category:LGBT actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French actress}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image              = Ad\u00e8le Haenel Cannes 2017.jpg\n| caption            = Haenel at the [[2017 Cannes Film Festival]]\n| name               = Ad\u00e8le Haenel\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=no|1989|2|11}}\n| birth_place        = [[Paris]], France\n| nationality        = French\n| occupation         = Actress\n| yearsactive        = 2002\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Ad\u00e8le Haenel''' ({{IPA-fr|ad\u025bl en\u025bl|lang}}; born 1 January 1989<ref name=MarieClaire>{{cite web |last=Bourdon |first=Megan |date=5 November 2019 |title=Ad\u00e8le Haenel, actrice sans fards et r\u00e9sistante |url=https://www.marieclaire.fr/adele-haenel,1324009.asp |newspaper=[[Marie Claire]] |language=French |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://madame.lefigaro.fr/personnalite/adele-haenel|title=Ad\u00e8le Haenel|work=Madame Figaro|accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Descamps|first=Quentin|date=13 March 2015|url=https://next.liberation.fr/cinema/2015/03/13/adele-haenel-la-belle-degenree_1220155|title=Ad\u00e8le Haenel, la belle d\u00e9genr\u00e9e|work=Lib\u00e9ration|accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rtl.fr/culture/cine-series/cesar-2015-adele-haenel-remporte-le-cesar-de-la-meilleure-actrice-7776692677|title=C\u00e9sar 2015 : Ad\u00e8le Haenel remporte le C\u00e9sar de la meilleure actrice|publisher=RTL|date=21 February 2015|accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref>) is a French actress. She is the recipient of several accolades, including two [[C\u00e9sar Award]]s from seven nominations and one [[Lumi\u00e8res Award]] from two nominations.\n\nHaenel began her career as a child actress, making her film debut with ''[[Les Diables]]'' (2002) at the age of 12, and quickly rose to prominence in the French entertainment industry as a teenager. She received her first C\u00e9sar Award nomination for her performance in ''[[Water Lilies (film)|Water Lilies]]'' (2007), which also marked the beginning of her long professional and personal relationship with director [[C\u00e9line Sciamma]]. In 2014, Haenel received her first C\u00e9sar Award for her supporting role in ''[[Suzanne (2013 film)|Suzanne]]'', and in 2015 won the [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Actress]] for ''[[Love at First Fight (film)|Love at First Fight]]''. She continued to garner recognition for her performances in ''[[BPM (Beats per Minute)]]'' (2017), ''[[The Trouble with You]]'' (2018) and ''[[Portrait of a Lady on Fire]]'' (2019).\n\n== Early life ==\nHaenel was born on 1 January 1989 in [[Paris]],<ref name=MarieClaire/> and grew up in [[Montreuil, Seine-Saint-Denis]] in what she described as \"a very left-wing, artistic neighborhood\".<ref name=FilmComment>{{cite web |date=24 May 2019 |last1=Rapold |first1=Nicolas |title=Interview: Ad\u00e8le Haenel |url=https://www.filmcomment.com/blog/cannes-interview-adele-haenel/ |newspaper=[[Film Comment]] |accessdate=7 January 2020}}</ref> Her mother is a teacher and her father is a translator.<ref name=MarieClaire/> She has Austrian heritage through her father and speaks some German.<ref name=FilmComment/><ref name=Grazia>{{cite web |last=Puyremond |first=Zo\u00e9 |date=7 February 2020 |title=8 choses que vous ne savez (peut-\u00eatre) pas sur Ad\u00e8le Haenel |url=https://www.grazia.fr/people/8-choses-que-vous-ne-savez-peut-etre-pas-sur-adele-haenel-949965 |newspaper=[[Grazia]] |language=French |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> Haenel started acting at the age of 5 and was involved in local theatre.<ref name=LeMondeGallot2014>{{cite web |last=Gallot |first=Cl\u00e9mentine |date=11 July 2014 |title=La belle vie d'Ad\u00e8le Haenel |url=https://www.lemonde.fr/m-actu/article/2014/07/11/la-belle-vie-d-adele_4454943_4497186.html |newspaper=[[Le Monde]] |language=French |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> As a child, Haenel would mimic cartoon characters, particularly the characters of [[Tex Avery]].<ref name=FranceInfo>{{cite web |last=Vandel |first=Philippe |date=14 November 2016 |title=Tout et son contraire. Ad\u00e8le Haenel: \"Je pr\u00e9f\u00e8re mettre un justaucorps vert plut\u00f4t que d'aller d\u00eener au Fouquet's\" |url=https://www.francetvinfo.fr/replay-radio/tout-et-son-contraire/tout-et-son-contraire-adele-haenel-je-prefere-mettre-un-juste-au-corps-vert-plutot-que-d-aller-diner-au-fouquet-s_1909935.html |newspaper=[[France Info (radio network)|France Info]] |language=French |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nHaenel studied economics and social sciences at the [[Lyc\u00e9e Montaigne (Paris)|Lyc\u00e9e Montaigne]].<ref name=Politiquelles>{{cite web |date=15 November 2019 |title=#3 Portraits de Femmes : Ad\u00e8le Haenel |url=https://politiquelles.org/3-portraits-de-femmes-adele-haenel/ |newspaper=Politiqu'elles |language=French |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> She had planned to attend [[HEC Paris]] and took a preparatory course, but ultimately failed the entrance exam.<ref name=Grazia/> Haenel continued her studies in economics and sociology, eventually receiving a master's degree.<ref name=Elle2012>{{cite web |date=30 March 2012  |title=Ad\u00e8le Haenel, actrice sans fards et r\u00e9sistante |url=https://www.elle.fr/People/La-vie-des-people/Une-journee-avec/Une-journee-avec-Adele-Haenel-1976016 |newspaper=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle ]] |language=French |accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref> She also pursued studies in physics and marine biology.<ref>{{cite web |last=M\u00e9dioni |first=Gilles |date=16 March 2016 |title=Les Ogres. Ad\u00e8le Haenel: \"Ne valorisons pas trop la souffrance\"  |url=https://www.lexpress.fr/culture/cinema/les-ogres-adele-haenel-ne-valorisons-pas-trop-la-souffrance_1769741.html |newspaper=[[L'Express]] |language=French |accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nHaenel made her film debut in 2002 at the age of 12, playing an autistic girl in the {{Interlanguage link|Christophe Ruggia|fr}} film ''[[Les Diables]]''.<ref name=Guardian2019Chrisafis>{{cite web |last=Chrisafis |first=Angelique |date=5 November 2019 |title=French actor Ad\u00e8le Haenel claims director sexually harassed her |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/05/french-actor-adele-haenel-alleges-she-was-sexually-harassed-by-director |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> She had been chosen for the lead role after accompanying her brother to the audition.<ref name=LExpress2014>{{cite web |last=M\u00e9dioni |first=Gilles |date=16 July 2014 |title=Qui est Ad\u00e8le Haenel, C\u00e9sar 2015 de la meilleure actrice? |url=https://www.lexpress.fr/culture/cinema/adele-haenel-star-nouvelle-generation_1554363.html |newspaper=[[L'Express]] |language=French |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> After ''Les Diables'', Haenel took a five-year break from acting.<ref name=MarieClaire/> In 2007, she was persuaded by casting director Christel Baras (who had cast her in her film debut) to resume her film career, taking up the part of a [[synchronised swimming|synchronised swimmer]] in [[C\u00e9line Sciamma]]'s debut feature ''[[Water Lilies (film)|Water Lilies]]''.<ref name=LExpress2014/> [[Manohla Dargis]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' highlighted Haenel's performance in an otherwise mixed review of the film, recognizing her as having \"the makings of a real star\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Dargis |first=Manohla |date=4 April 2008 |title=Crossing Into the Deep End, Where Desire Is Fathomed |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/04/movies/04lili.html?ref=movies |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> For her role in the film, Haenel was nominated for the [[C\u00e9sar Award for Most Promising Actress]] in 2008.<ref name=Crash>{{cite web |last=Leturcq |first=Armelle |date=5 November 2019 |title=Adele Haenel on Film |url=https://www.crash.fr/adele-haenel-on-film-crash-magazine/ |newspaper=[[Crash Magazine]] |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> In 2012, she was nominated in the same category for ''[[House of Tolerance]]'' (2011),<ref name=Cesar2012>{{cite web |last=Tartaglione |first=Nancy |date=25 January 2012 |title='The Artist' Nabs 10 C\u00e9sar Nominations, But Maiwenn's 'Poliss' Leads With 13 Nods |url=https://deadline.com/2012/01/artist-nabs-10-cesar-nominations-but-maiwenns-poliss-leads-with-13-nods-221370/ |newspaper=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> a period film directed by [[Bertrand Bonello]], in which she played a prostitute at an upscale Parisian brothel at the turn of the twentieth century.<ref name=ArtForum>{{cite web |last=Anderson |first=Melissa |date=1 June 2018 |title=French, Open: Melissa Anderson on Ad\u00e8le Haenel |url=https://www.artforum.com/print/201806/melissa-anderson-on-adele-haenel-75512 |newspaper=[[Artforum]] |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> She also received the [[Lumi\u00e8res Award for Most Promising Actress]] along with her co-stars [[C\u00e9line Sallette]] and Alice Barnole.<ref name=Lumiere2012>{{cite web |last=Leffler |first=Rebecca |date=13 January 2012 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/the-artist-lumiere-awards-281420 |title='The Artist' Named Best Film at France's Lumiere Awards |accessdate=1 March 2020 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ad\u00e8le Haenel C\u00e9sars 2014.jpg|thumb|Haenel in 2014, receiving her first C\u00e9sar Award for ''[[Suzanne (2013 film)|Suzanne]]'']]\n\nHaenel played one of the two sisters in [[Katell Quill\u00e9v\u00e9r\u00e9]]'s ''[[Suzanne (2013 film)|Suzanne]]'' (2013),<ref name=ArtForum/> for which she received the [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Supporting Actress]].<ref name=Cesar2014>{{cite web |last=Richford |first=Rhonda |date=28 February 2014 |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cesar-awards-winners-list-684357 |title=France's Cesar Awards: ''Me, Myself and Mum'' Wins Best Film |accessdate=3 May 2014 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref> In 2014, Haenel starred in the [[Thomas Cailley]] romantic comedy ''[[Love at First Fight (film)|Love at First Fight]]'' as Madeleine, a graduate-school dropout and [[Survivalism|survivalist]].<ref name=ArtForum/> She won the [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Actress]] for her performance.<ref name=Cesar2015>{{cite web|last=Richford |first=Rhonda |date=20 February 2015 |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/2015-cesar-awards-winners-list-775695|title=Cesar Awards: 'Timbktu' Sweeps, Kristen Stewart Makes History|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> In the same year, Haenel co-starred with [[Catherine Deneuve]] in [[Andr\u00e9 T\u00e9chin\u00e9]]'s crime drama ''[[In the Name of My Daughter]]'', playing the daughter of a casino owner. Writing for ''[[The Village Voice]]'', Melissa Anderson compared her performance to that of [[Isabelle Adjani]]'s in the 1970s and '80s, and declared her a worthy successor to Deneuve in French cinema.<ref>{{cite web |last=Anderson |first=Melissa |date=20 May 2015 |url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2015/05/20/in-love-at-first-fight-adele-haenel-burns-through-our-screens/ |title=In Love at First Fight, Adele Haenel Burns Through Our Screens |accessdate=1 March 2020 |work=[[The Village Voice]]}}</ref> For her roles in both films, Hanael received a [[Lumi\u00e8res Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] nomination at the [[20th Lumi\u00e8res Awards]].<ref name=Lumiere2015>{{cite web |last=Richford |first=Rhonda |date=12 January 2015 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/frances-lumiere-awards-nominations-unveiled-762567 |title=France's Lumiere Awards Nominations Unveiled |accessdate=1 March 2020 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 Haenel made her German language debut in the film ''[[The Bloom of Yesterday]]'' playing the French descendant of German Holocaust survivors.\n\nIn the 2017 [[Robin Campillo]] film ''[[BPM (Beats per Minute)]]'', Haenel portrayed Sophie, a headstrong [[HIV/AIDS]] activist of the Paris chapter of [[ACT UP]].<ref name=ArtForum/> She received a nomination for the C\u00e9sar Award for Best Supporting Actress for her performance.<ref name=Cesar2018>{{cite web|last=Richford |first=Rhonda |date=2 March 2018 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/cesar-awards-2018-winners-list-1089548/item/best-film-1079713|title=Cesar Awards: '120 BPM' Takes Six Awards Including Best Film|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nHaenel starred in the 2018 [[Pierre Salvadori]] crime comedy ''[[The Trouble with You]]'', playing a widowed detective based on the [[French Riviera]]. David Rooney of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' noted her performance as evoking the \"classic screwball heroine\", a departure from her usually more serious roles, and complimented her on the \"grace and buoyancy\" she brought to the character.<ref>{{cite web |date=15 May 2018 |last=Rooney |first=David |title='The Trouble With You' ('En Liberte!'): Film Review Cannes 2018 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/trouble-with-you-en-liberte-cannes-2018-1112275 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> She was again nominated for the [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Actress]].<ref name=Cesar2019>{{cite web |date=January 23, 2019 |last=Keslassy |first=Elsa |title=\u2018Sink or Swim,\u2019 \u2018Custody\u2019 Lead Race for France\u2019s Cesar Awards |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/cesar-nominations-sink-or-swim-custody-lead-race-1203115394/ |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Haenel appeared in three films which played at the [[2019 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes Film Festival]]: [[Mr. Oizo|Quentin Dupieux]]'s ''[[Deerskin (film)|Deerskin]]'', Aude L\u00e9a Rapin's ''Heroes Don't Die'', and C\u00e9line Sciamma's ''[[Portrait of a Lady on Fire]]''.<ref>{{cite web |date=May 20, 2019  |last=Lodge |first=Guy |title=Cannes Film Review: \u2018Heroes Don\u2019t Die\u2019 |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/reviews/heroes-dont-die-review-1203221561/ |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> In ''Portrait of a Lady on Fire'', Haenel portrayed H\u00e9lo\u00efse, a young aristocrat in 18th-century [[Brittany]] who is to be married off to a nobleman from Milan. ''[[The New Yorker]]'''s [[Richard Brody]] took note of her chemistry with co-star [[No\u00e9mie Merlant]] and complimented the actresses for being \"relentlessly graceful, endowed with physical aplomb, contemplative insight, and strong emotion\".<ref>{{cite web |date=December 10, 2019 |last=Brody |first=Richard |title=Speaking for Women\u2019s Art in \u201cPortrait of a Lady on Fire\u201d |url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/the-front-row/speaking-for-womens-art-in-portrait-of-a-lady-on-fire-review |website=[[The New Yorker]] |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> [[A. O. Scott]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' considered Haenel's performance worthy of an Oscar nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]],<ref>{{cite web |date=3 January 2020 |last1=Dargis |first1=Manohla |last2=Scott |first2=A.O. |title=And the 2020 Oscar Nominees Should Be \u2026 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/01/03/movies/critics-oscar-nominees.html?searchResultPosition=14 |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> and [[Bilge Ebiri]] of ''[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]'' described the climax of the film (which features Haenel) as \"one of the finest pieces of acting and one of the most moving images I\u2019ve seen in eons.\"<ref>{{cite web |date=12 February 2020 |last1=Ebiri |first1=Bilge |title=Portrait of a Lady on Fire Is a Grand, Capital-R Romance |url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/02/portrait-of-a-lady-on-fire-movie-review.html |website=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]] |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> Haenel was nominated for the [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Actress]] for her performance, her seventh C\u00e9sar nomination.<ref name=Cesar2020Nom>{{cite web |date=January 29, 2020 |last1=Tartaglione |first1=Nancy |title=C\u00e9sar Awards Nominations: Roman Polanski\u2019s \u2018An Officer And A Spy\u2019 Leads With 12; Ladj Ly\u2019s \u2018Les Mis\u00e9rables\u2019 Scores 11 \u2013 Full List |url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/cesar-awards-nominations-2020-roman-polanski-les-miserables-portrait-of-a-lady-on-fire-full-list-1202845041/ |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2014, Haenel [[Coming out|came out]] as lesbian during her C\u00e9sar award acceptance speech and acknowledged her relationship with director [[C\u00e9line Sciamma]], whom she met on the set of ''Water Lilies''.<ref name=\"JRomney\">{{cite web |first=Jonathan|last=Romney|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2016/dec/04/adele-haenel-unknown-girl-inteview-dardenne|title=Adele Haenel, 'Recycling cliches is a sign that a film lacks courage' |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=4 December 2016 |access-date=8 December 2016}}</ref> The couple amicably split in 2018, shortly before they began work on ''Portrait of a Lady on Fire''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Erbland |first1=Kate |title=\u2018Portrait of a Lady on Fire\u2019 Filmmaker C\u00e9line Sciamma Is Trying to Break Your Heart |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/portrait-of-a-lady-on-fire-filmmaker-celine-sciamma-interview-1202193537/ |accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref> In 2018, she was in a relationship with musician and singer Julia Lano\u00eb from the band [[Sexy Sushi]]. \n\nHaenel identifies as a [[feminist]].<ref name=MarieClaire/> She is a prominent face of France's [[Me Too movement|#MeToo]] movement,<ref name=\"RT\">{{cite web |title=MeToo movement |url=https://www.rt.com/news/481980-cesar-awards-polanski-metoo/ |website=rt.com |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web |last=Schofield|first=Hugh|date=7 November 2019|title=Ad\u00e8le Haenel MeToo moment shocks French cinema |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-50322452 |website=[[BBC]] |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> and was the first prominent actress to speak publicly about abuse within the French film industry.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite web |last=Peltier|first=Elian|date=24 February 2020|title=Ad\u00e8le Haenel: France \u2018Missed the Boat\u2019 on #MeToo |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/24/movies/adele-haenel-france-metoo.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> In a November 2019 ''[[Mediapart]]'' interview, Haenel accused director Christophe Ruggia of [[sexual harassment|sexually harassing]] her from the time she was 12 to 15 after casting her in his film ''Les Diables''.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Chu |first1=Henry |last2=Keslassy|first2=Elsa |title=\u2018Portrait of a Lady on Fire\u2019 Star Adele Haenel Accuses Director of Years of Harassment |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/global/portrait-of-a-lady-on-fire-adele-haenel-accuses-christophe-ruggia-harassment-1203391576/ |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=4 November 2019|accessdate=4 November 2019}}</ref> Following the experience, she considered abandoning acting altogether.<ref name=Guardian2019Chrisafis/> Haenel's account was backed up by many people who had worked on the film and noted Ruggia's inappropriate behaviour towards her, along with letters he had written her at the time proclaiming his love for her.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Grater |first1=Tom |title=French Actress Ad\u00e8le Haenel Accuses Director Christophe Ruggia Of Sexually Harassing Her From Age 12; He Denies Allegations |url=https://deadline.com/2019/11/portrait-of-a-lady-on-fire-adele-haenel-accuses-french-director-christophe-ruggia-underage-sexual-harassment-1202776553/ |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=4 November 2019|accessdate=4 November 2019}}</ref> As a result Ruggia was expelled from the Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des r\u00e9alisateurs de films, the guild for French directors.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mintzer |first1=Jordan |title=Christophe Ruggia, French Filmmaker Accused of Sexual Harassment, Is Fired From Directors\u2019 Association |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/christophe-ruggia-accused-sexually-harassing-actress-adele-haenel-1252232 |magazine=[[Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Eldridge Industries]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=4 November 2019|accessdate=4 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"\u201ccnn\u201d\">{{cite web|first=Saskya|last=Vandoorne|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/11/07/europe/adele-haenel-sexual-abuse-claims-intl/index.html|title=French film star Adele Haenel accuses director of abuse|website=[[CNN]]|publisher=[[Turner Broadcasting Systems]]|location=Atlanta, Georgia|date=8 November 2019|accessdate=23 November 2019}}</ref><ref>O'Connor, Roisin (7 November 2019). [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/adele-haenel-sexual-harassment-christophe-ruggia-director-teenager-france-a9188881.html \"Adele Haenel: French film industry rocked by childhood sexual harassment allegations against director Christophe Ruggia.\"] ''[[The Independent]]''. Retrieved 1 March 2020.</ref> Though Haenel had explicitly chosen not to go to the police with her accusations, citing the justice system as \"usually condemning so few sexual offenders\" and \"only one rape out of a hundred\" and stating that \"the justice ignores us, we ignore the justice\",<ref name=Mediapart>{{cite web |last=Turchi |first=Marine |date=3 November 2019 |title=#MeToo dans le cin\u00e9ma: l\u2019actrice Ad\u00e8le Haenel brise un nouveau tabou |url=https://www.mediapart.fr/journal/france/031119/metoo-dans-le-cinema-l-actrice-adele-haenel-brise-un-nouveau-tabou?page_article=1, |newspaper=[[Mediapart]] |language=French |url-access=subscription |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> the publicity garnered by her interviews about the abuse led the Paris prosecutor's office to announce they were investigating Ruggia.<ref name=\u201ccnn\u201d/> Haenel later changed her mind about working with the police and officially filed a complaint against Ruggia in late November 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=KESLASSY |first1=ELSA |title=Adele Haenel Files Police Complaint Against French Director |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/adele-haenel-police-complaint-against-french-director-christophe-ruggia-1203416872/ |accessdate=7 January 2020}}</ref> In January 2020, the police officially charged Ruggia with sexual aggression against a minor by a person of authority and sexual harassment.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Grater |first1=Tom |title=French Director Christophe Ruggia Formally Charged By Paris Prosecutors In Adele Haenel Sexual Assault Case |url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/french-director-christophe-ruggia-formally-charged-paris-prosecutors-adele-haenel-1202832599/}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 February 2020, Haenel walked out of the [[45th C\u00e9sar Awards]] ceremony after [[Roman Polanski]], who was [[Roman Polanski sexual abuse case|convicted of raping 13-year old Samantha Geimer]], won the award for [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Director|Best Director]] for his film ''[[An Officer and a Spy (film)|An Officer and a Spy]]''. As Haenel left, she cried \u201cShame!\u201d, and after exiting the auditorium, she was filmed clapping sarcastically and shouting \"Bravo la p\u00e9dophilie!\" (\"Well done, paedophilia!\").<ref name=\"MadameFigaro2020\">{{cite web |date=29 February 2020 |title=\"Bravo la p\u00e9dophilie\" : le coup de col\u00e8re d'Ad\u00e8le Haenel apr\u00e8s la victoire de Roman Polanski aux C\u00e9sar |url=https://madame.lefigaro.fr/societe/on-est-un-peu-tendues-celine-sciamma-et-adele-haenel-sexpriment-sur-la-polemique-roman-polanski-aux-cesar-280220-180093 |website=[[Madame Figaro]] |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n|-\n| 2002 || ''[[Les Diables]]'' || Chlo\u00e9 || \n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[Water Lilies (film)|Water Lilies]]'' || Floriane || \n|-\n| 2009 || ''D\u00e9cha\u00een\u00e9es'' || Lucie || TV movie\n|-\n| 2010 || ''Adieu Molitor'' || La copine de Paulin  || Short film\n|-\n| 2010 || ''Les Grandes For\u00eats'' || Lise || Short film\n|-\n| 2010 || ''Pauline'' || || Short film\n|-\n| 2011 || ''[[Iris in Bloom]]'' || Isabelle || \n|-\n| 2011 || ''[[House of Tolerance]]'' || L\u00e9a || \n|-\n| 2011 || ''[[Heat Wave (2011 film)|Heat Wave]]'' || Am\u00e9lie || \n|-\n| 2011 || ''Les Enfantants de la Nuit''  || Heriette || Short film\n|-\n| 2011 || ''Goldman'' || Jeanne || TV movie \n|-\n| 2012 || ''Folks'' ||  || Short film\n|-\n| 2012 || ''[[Alyah]]'' || Jeanne ||