{"title_page": "Ficus deltoidea", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox \n| name = Mas Cotek\n| image = Ficus deltoidea.jpg\n| image_caption = ''Ficus deltoidea'' at [[Olbrich Botanical Gardens]], [[Madison, WI]]\n| genus = Ficus\n| subgenus = [[Ficus subg. Ficus|Ficus]]\n| species = deltoidea\n| authority = [[William Jack (botanist)|Jack]]\n}}\n\n'''''Ficus deltoidea''''', commonly known as '''mistletoe fig''' (''mas cotek'' in [[Malay language|Malaysian]], ''tabat barito'' in [[Indonesia]], or ''\u0e2a\u0e32\u0e25\u0e34\u0e01\u0e32\u0e25\u0e34\u0e49\u0e19\u0e17\u0e2d\u0e07'' in [[Thai language|Thai]]) is a [[species]] of [[flowering plant]] in the [[family (botany)|family]] [[Moraceae]], native to [[Southeast Asia]], and widely naturalized in other parts of the world.\n\n==Description==\n''F. deltoidea'' is an [[evergreen]] shrub or small tree, growing up to about 2 m tall, with thick leaves that are deltoid in shape, rounded at the apex and tapering at the base.<ref name=\"FELDA\">{{ cite book |last=Hassan |first=W. E. |date=2006 |title=Healing Herbs of Malaysia |publisher=Kuala Lumpur: Federal Land Development Agency |isbn=9789839954425}}</ref> The upper surface of the plants' leaves are dark, shining green, while the lower surface is golden yellow with black spots. Male and female plants are physically distinctive, with the leaves of female plants being big and round, while the leaves of male plants are small, round and long.<ref name=\"FELDA\" /> ''F. deltoidea'' can grow on the land ([[terrestrial plant]]), on the stone ([[Lithophyte]]) or attach to other plants as [[epiphyte]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal |last=Agustina |first=A. |last2=Zuhud |first2=E.A.M. |last3=Darusman |first3=L.K. |date=April 2015 |title=Characteristics of Tabat Barito (Ficus deltoidea Jack) Microhabitat on Their Host Plants |journal=Jurnal Penelitian Hutan Dan Konservasi Alam |volume=12 |issue=1 |pages=89\u2013104 |doi=10.20886/jphka.2015.12.1.89-104 }}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal |last=Corner |first=E.J.H. |date=November 20, 1969 |title=The Complex of Ficus deltoidea; A Recent Invasion of the Sunda Shelf |journal=Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London. Series B, Biological Sciences |volume=256 |issue=808 |pages=281\u2013317  |jstor=2416885 |doi=10.1098/rstb.1969.0043|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/809dc528b9a2d9a6205a8ae7cf8d62c9987d57b4 }}</ref> The plant grows wild in eastern [[peninsular Malaysia]] ([[Kelantan]], [[Terengganu]]),  [[Sumatra]], [[Java]], [[Borneo]] ([[Sabah]], [[Sarawak]], [[Brunei]] and [[Kalimantan]]), [[Sulawesi|Celebes]], [[Palawan]] and in [[Mindanao]] and is used by the traditional medical practitioners in these regions.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Taxonomy ==\n[[Cornelis Christiaan Berg|C.C. Berg]] in his publication in [[Blumea (journal)|Blumea]] classified ''F. deltoidea'' into two sub species based on difference of the leaf shape, subsp. ''deltoidea'' and subsp. ''motleyana'' (Miq.) C.C. Berg''.''<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal |last=Berg |first=C.C. |date=November 28, 2003 |title=Flora Malesiana precursor for the treatment of Moraceae 3: Ficus subgenus Ficus |url=http://repository.naturalis.nl/document/566488 |journal=Blumea |volume=48 |issue=3 |pages=529\u2013550 |doi=10.3767/000651903X489537 |via=Naturalis}}</ref> ''F. deltoidea'' subsp. ''deltoidea'' has board leaf shape variation from obtriangular to linear-oblanceolate, include apex and based on lamina variation in the common deltoid shape with furcate midrib. ''F. deltoidea'' subsp. ''motleyana'' has oblong to lanceolate lamina shape with pinnately vein.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Flora Malesiana Series I (Seed Plants) Volume 17 Part 2: Moraceae-Ficus |last=Berg |first=C.C. |last2=Corner |first2=E.J.H. |publisher=National Herbarium of the Netherlands |year=2005 |isbn=978-9071236617 |location=Leiden |pages=90\u201394}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> The first subspecies with deltoid leaf shape is a common taxa to be used as medicinal plant. Lee et al. (2016) success to conduct molecular analysis with [[cpDNA]] and nSSR marker system for ''F. deltoidea'' from Peninsular Malaysia and the result support taxonomy classification based on morphological traits.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Tnah |first=Lee Hong |last2=Lee |first2=Soon Leong |last3=Tan |first3=Ai Lee |last4=Lee |first4=Chai Ting |last5=Ng |first5=Kevin Kit Siong |last6=Ng |first6=Chin Hong |title=Intraspecific classification of Ficus deltoidea Jack subsp. deltoidea (Moraceae) in Peninsular Malaysia based on morphological and molecular variations |journal=Biochemical Systematics and Ecology |volume=67 |pages=119\u2013128 |doi=10.1016/j.bse.2016.06.001 |year=2016}}</ref>\n\n==Uses==\n''Ficus deltoides'' is used as an ornamental plant, requiring the protection of glass during winter months, in zones where the temperature falls below {{convert|10|C|F|abbr=on}}. It requires a sunny, sheltered, south- or east-facing position.<ref name = RHSPF/> In the UK it is a recipient of  the [[Royal Horticultural Society]]'s [[Award of Garden Merit]].<ref name = RHSPF>{{cite web \n| url = https://www.rhs.org.uk/Plants/7200/Ficus-deltoidea/Details | title = ''Ficus deltoides'' | website = www.rhs.org | publisher = Royal Horticultural Society | accessdate = 27 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.rhs.org.uk/plants/pdfs/agm-lists/agm-ornamentals.pdf | title = AGM Plants - Ornamental | date = November 2018 | page = 1009 | publisher = Royal Horticultural Society | website = www.rhs.org | accessdate = 27 February 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe plant is used in traditional medicine in eastern Peninsular Malaysia and Borneo, where its [[leaf|leaves]], [[fruit]]s, [[Plant stem|stems]] and [[root]]s are believed to have healing properties. Among the traditional uses attributed to this plant include menstrual cycle regulation; the treatment of post-partum depression, lung diseases, high blood pressure, diabetes, and skin problems;<ref name=\"FELDA\" /> as well as an aphrodisiac for both men and women.<ref>{{cite book |last=Bodeker |first=G. |title=Health and Beauty from the Rainforest: Malaysian Traditions of Ramuan |year=2009 |publisher=Didier Millet |location=Kuala Lumpur |isbn=978-981-4217-91-0}}</ref>\n\n''F. deltoidea'' has been commercialized in the region of its origin, where it is used as an ingredient in herbal drinks, coffee drinks, supplements, and massage oils.\n\n==Chemical composition==\n''F. deltoidea'' has been reported to possess [[triterpenoid saponins|triterpenoids]], [[antinociceptive]], [[anti-inflammatory]], [[antioxidant]] and natural phenols ([[flavonoid]]s and [[proanthocyanin]]s, a type of condensed tannins).<ref>{{cite journal |first=Elham |last=Farsi |date=2014 |title=Preclinical evaluation of antidiabetic properties of Ficus deltoidea |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/263810939 |publisher=Lambert Academic Publishing }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Sulaiman |first=M.R. |last2=Hussain |first2=M.K. |last3=Zakaria |first3=Z.A. |last4=Somchit |first4=M.N. |last5=Moin |first5=S. |last6=Mohamad |first6=A.S. |last7=Israf |first7=D.A. |title=Evaluation of the antinociceptive activity of Ficus deltoidea aqueous extract |journal=Fitoterapia |volume=79 |issue=7\u20138 |pages=557\u2013561 |doi=10.1016/j.fitote.2008.06.005 |pmid=18672036 |year=2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Abdullah |first=Z. |last2=Hussain |first2=K. |last3=Zhari |first3=I. |last4=Rasadah |first4=M.A. |date=December 2009 |title=Anti-inflammatory Activity of Standardised Extracts of Leaves of Three Varieties of Ficus deltoidea |url=http://impactfactor.org/PDF/IJPCR/1/IJPCR,Vol1,Issue3,Article3.pdf |journal=International Journal of Pharmaceutical and Clinical Research |volume=1 |issue=3 |pages=100\u2013105 |via=Impact Factor}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Choo |first=C.Y. |last2=Sulong |first2=N.Y. |last3=Man |first3=F. |last4=Wong |first4=T.W. |title=Vitexin and isovitexin from the Leaves of Ficus deltoidea with in-vivo \u03b1-glucosidase inhibition |journal=Journal of Ethnopharmacology |volume=142 |issue=3 |pages=776\u2013781 |doi=10.1016/j.jep.2012.05.062 |pmid=22683902 |year=2012}}</ref> Leaf extract treatment to mice indicated decrease of blood sugar level into 32.54% compared to mice without treatment<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Cahyanto |first=H.A. |last2=Supriyatna |first2=N. |date=2013 |title=Anti-diabetic Activity of Tabat Barito Leafs (Ficus deltoidea, Jack) Extract in Rats |url=http://ejournal.kemenperin.go.id/biopropal/article/view/805/720 |journal=Biopropal |publisher=Balai Riset dan Standardisasi Industri Pontianak |volume=4 |issue=1 |pages=17\u201321 |via=Neliti}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q406938}}\n\n[[Category:Medicinal plants of Asia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox \n| name = Mas Cotek\n| image = Ficus deltoidea.jpg\n| image_caption = ''Ficus deltoidea'' at [[Olbrich Botanical Gardens]], [[Madison, WI]]\n| genus = Ficus\n| subgenus = [[Ficus subg. Ficus|Ficus]]\n| species = deltoidea\n| authority = [[William Jack (botanist)|Jack]]\n}}\n\n'''''Ficus deltoidea''''', commonly known as '''mistletoe fig''' (''mas cotek'' in [[Malay language|Malaysian]], ''tabat barito'' in [[Indonesia]], or ''\u0e2a\u0e32\u0e25\u0e34\u0e01\u0e32\u0e25\u0e34\u0e49\u0e19\u0e17\u0e2d\u0e07'' in [[Thai language|Thai]]) is a [[species]] of [[flowering plant]] in the [[family (botany)|family]] [[Moraceae]], native to [[Southeast Asia]], and widely naturalized in other parts of the world.\n\n==Description==\n''F. deltoidea'' is an [[evergreen]] shrub or small tree, growing up to about 2 m tall, with thick leaves that are deltoid in shape, rounded at the apex and tapering at the base.<ref name=\"FELDA\">{{ cite book |last=Hassan |first=W. E. |date=2006 |title=Healing Herbs of Malaysia |publisher=Kuala Lumpur: Federal Land Development Agency |isbn=9789839954425}}</ref> The upper surface of the plants' leaves are dark, shining green, while the lower surface is golden yellow with black spots. Male and female plants are physically distinctive, with the leaves of female plants being big and round, while the leaves of male plants are small, round and long.<ref name=\"FELDA\" /> ''F. deltoidea'' can grow on the land ([[terrestrial plant]]), on the stone ([[Lithophyte]]) or attach to other plants as [[epiphyte]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal |last=Agustina |first=A. |last2=Zuhud |first2=E.A.M. |last3=Darusman |first3=L.K. |date=April 2015 |title=Characteristics of Tabat Barito (Ficus deltoidea Jack) Microhabitat on Their Host Plants |journal=Jurnal Penelitian Hutan Dan Konservasi Alam |volume=12 |issue=1 |pages=89\u2013104 |doi=10.20886/jphka.2015.12.1.89-104 }}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal |last=Corner |first=E.J.H. |date=November 20, 1969 |title=The Complex of Ficus deltoidea; A Recent Invasion of the Sunda Shelf |journal=Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London. Series B, Biological Sciences |volume=256 |issue=808 |pages=281\u2013317  |jstor=2416885 |doi=10.1098/rstb.1969.0043|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/809dc528b9a2d9a6205a8ae7cf8d62c9987d57b4 }}</ref> The plant grows wild in eastern [[peninsular Malaysia]] ([[Kelantan]], [[Terengganu]]),  [[Sumatra]], [[Java]], [[Borneo]] ([[Sabah]], [[Sarawak]], [[Brunei]] and [[Kalimantan]]), [[Sulawesi|Celebes]], [[Palawan]] and in [[Mindanao]] and is used by the traditional medical practitioners in these regions.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Taxonomy ==\n[[Cornelis Christiaan Berg|C.C. Berg]] in his publication in [[Blumea (journal)|Blumea]] classified ''F. deltoidea'' into two sub species based on difference of the leaf shape, subsp. ''deltoidea'' and subsp. ''motleyana'' (Miq.) C.C. Berg''.''<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal |last=Berg |first=C.C. |date=November 28, 2003 |title=Flora Malesiana precursor for the treatment of Moraceae 3: Ficus subgenus Ficus |url=http://repository.naturalis.nl/document/566488 |journal=Blumea |volume=4